window.studyGuideContent["ob_cheatsheet"] = "# OB Cheat Sheet: Fetal Development, Prenatal Care & Pregnancy Adaptations\n### Chapters 3, 4 & 5 \u2014 Quick Review\n\n---\n\n## \ud83e\uddec FETAL DEVELOPMENT (Ch. 3)\n\n### Cell Division\n| Term | Definition |\n|------|-----------|\n| **Meiosis** | Reduces chromosomes to **23** (sex cells) |\n| **Mitosis** | Copies all **46** chromosomes (body growth) |\n\n### Fertilization \u2192 Implantation Timeline\n| Stage | What Happens |\n|-------|-------------|\n| **Fertilization** | Sperm + ovum unite in **outer third of fallopian tube** |\n| **Zygote** | Single fertilized cell |\n| **Morula** | Solid ball of 16-32 cells; enters uterus by **day 3** |\n| **Blastocyst** | Floats 2-4 more days, then **implants** (upper posterior uterine wall) |\n| **Decidua** | Endometrium after implantation; **decidua basalis** = maternal part of placenta |\n\n> \ud83d\udd11 Sperm survive **5 days**, ovum survives **24 hours**. Sex determined at fertilization (XX or XY).\n\n### Three Germ Layers\n| Layer | Develops Into | Memory Aid |\n|-------|-------------|------------|\n| **Ectoderm** (outer) | Skin, hair, nails, nervous system, sense organs, mouth/anus lining | **E**cto = **E**xterior |\n| **Mesoderm** (middle) | Skeleton, muscles, blood vessels, kidneys, gonads | **M**eso = **M**uscle |\n| **Endoderm** (inner) | Trachea, bronchi, GI tract lining, bladder, urethra | **En**do = **In**ternal linings |\n\n### Key Milestones\n- **8 weeks**: All body systems formed, human appearance, enters **fetal period**\n- **20 weeks**: **Age of viability** (textbook); clinical viability ~22-24 weeks\n- **37 weeks**: Term (obstetrical); **39-40 weeks** = full term\n- **Amniotic fluid**: 30 mL (10wk) \u2192 350 mL (20wk) \u2192 **1000 mL (37wk)**\n\n### Placenta \u2014 \"Temporary Endocrine Organ\"\n**Four Hormones:**\n| Hormone | Function |\n|---------|----------|\n| **Progesterone** | Maintains uterine lining, \u2193 contractions, preps breasts for lactation |\n| **Estrogen** | \u2191 Uterine growth, \u2191 blood flow, breast duct development |\n| **hCG** | Signals conception, maintains corpus luteum; detected by pregnancy tests (7-9 days post-fertilization) |\n| **hPL** | \u2193 Maternal insulin sensitivity \u2192 more glucose for fetus (\"diabetogenic\") |\n\n### Umbilical Cord\n> **2 arteries, 1 vein** \u2014 covered by **Wharton jelly** \u2014 ~55 cm (22 in)\n> - **Arteries** = waste AWAY from fetus\n> - **Vein** = oxygenated blood TO fetus\n\n### Three Fetal Shunts \u2b50\n| Shunt | Bypasses | Closes After Birth |\n|-------|---------|-------------------|\n| **Ductus venosus** | Liver | When cord cut (permanent ~1 week) |\n| **Foramen ovale** | Lungs (R\u2192L atrium) | **2 hours** (permanent ~3 months) |\n| **Ductus arteriosus** | Lungs (pulm artery\u2192aorta) | **15 hours** (permanent ~3 weeks) |\n\n> After permanent closure \u2192 become **ligaments**\n\n### Twins\n- **Monozygotic** = identical, 1 egg, shared chorion/placenta\n- **Dizygotic** = fraternal, 2 eggs + 2 sperm, separate placentas (may fuse)\n\n### Teratogens\nAgents causing embryo malformation: medications, smoking, alcohol, undernutrition, infections\n\n---\n\n## \ud83e\udd30 PRENATAL CARE & ADAPTATIONS (Ch. 4)\n\n### Gravida/Para Terminology\n| Term | Meaning |\n|------|---------|\n| **Gravida** | # of pregnancies |\n| **Para** | # of births \u226520 weeks (alive or still) |\n| **GTPAL** | Gravida, Term, Preterm, Abortions, Living |\n| **Nullipara** | Never given birth past 20 weeks |\n| **Multipara** | 2+ births past 20 weeks |\n\n### N\u00e4gele's Rule (EDD Calculation) \u2b50\n> **LMP \u2212 3 months + 7 days**\n> Example: LMP May 5 \u2192 EDD = **February 12**\n\n### Signs of Pregnancy\n\n| Presumptive (subjective) | Probable (objective) | Positive (definitive) |\n|-------------------------|---------------------|----------------------|\n| Amenorrhea | Goodell sign (cervix softens) | Fetal heartbeat heard |\n| Nausea/vomiting | Chadwick sign (purplish cervix) | Fetal movement felt by examiner |\n| Breast tenderness | Hegar sign (lower uterus softens) | Fetus visible on ultrasound |\n| Fatigue, urinary frequency | Positive pregnancy test (hCG) | |\n| Quickening (mom feels movement) | Braxton Hicks contractions | |\n| Deepening pigmentation | Ballottement, abdominal enlargement | |\n\n### Routine Prenatal Labs by Trimester\n**1st Trimester**: Blood type/Rh, antibody screen, CBC, RPR (syphilis), rubella titer, TB screen, Hep B, HIV, UA/culture, Pap, chlamydia/gonorrhea, HbA1C, genetic screening (NIPT)\n\n**2nd Trimester**: Quad screen, anatomy ultrasound, glucose challenge test (GDM screening 24-28wk)\n\n**3rd Trimester**: GBS culture (35-37wk), repeat STI/HIV if indicated, NST/BPP, cervical fetal fibronectin\n\n### Every Prenatal Visit\nVital signs + weight, urinalysis (glucose/protein), fundal height, FHR, Leopold maneuvers (late pregnancy), risk factors, nutrition, discomforts\n\n### Four Critical Nutrients in Pregnancy\n| Nutrient | Daily Need | Key Points |\n|----------|-----------|------------|\n| **Protein** | 60 g/day | Meat, fish, poultry, dairy |\n| **Calcium** | 1000 mg | Dairy, leafy greens; needs Vit D |\n| **Iron** | 30 mg/day | 2x non-pregnant; prevents anemia |\n| **Folic acid** | 400 mcg daily | Prevents **neural tube defects** (B vitamin) |\n\n> \ud83d\udc8a **Ferrous sulfate (iron)**: Take with **orange juice** (vitamin C enhances absorption). Causes dark stools and constipation. Do NOT take with milk, antacids, or calcium.\n> \u26a0\ufe0f **Excess Vitamin A = teratogenic** (fetal anomalies/cardiac defects)\n> \ud83d\udca1 **Vitamin B6 + ginger** = recommended for pregnancy nausea\n> \ud83d\udeab **PICA** = craving/eating non-food substances (clay, starch, ice)\n\n### Normal Weight Gain: ~25-35 lbs (normal BMI)\n\n### Fundal Height Landmarks \u2b50\n- At **20 weeks**: fundus at **umbilicus**\n- **After delivery**: fundus at umbilicus, then descends 1-2 cm/day\n- Fundal height (in cm) \u2248 gestational age (weeks) from 20-36 weeks\n\n### Pregnancy Blood Values (vs. Non-Pregnant)\n| Lab | Pregnant | Non-Pregnant |\n|-----|----------|-------------|\n| Hgb | **11-12** g/dL | 12-16 |\n| Hct | 33-46% | 36-48% |\n| WBC | **5,000-15,000** | 5,000-10,000 |\n| Fibrinogen | **300-600** mg/dL | 200-400 |\n\n### Supine Hypotension Syndrome\n> Uterus compresses **inferior vena cava** when lying flat \u2192 \u2193 BP, dizziness\n> **Fix: Turn to LEFT SIDE**\n\n### Exercise: OK vs. Avoid\n\u2705 Walking, swimming, low-impact\n\ud83d\udeab Hot tubs, saunas, scuba, skiing, horseback riding, contact sports\n\n### Travel Safety\n- Seatbelt: **lap belt UNDER belly**, shoulder strap between breasts\n- Frequent breaks, hydration, ROM exercises (DVT prevention)\n\n### Common Discomforts & Remedies\n| Discomfort | Interventions |\n|-----------|--------------|\n| Nausea | Small frequent meals, crackers before rising, B6 + ginger |\n| Heartburn | Small meals, avoid lying down after eating, antacids if approved |\n| Constipation | Fluids, fiber, exercise (normal in pregnancy \u2014 progesterone slows GI) |\n| Leg cramps | Dorsiflex foot, calcium/magnesium |\n| Fatigue | Rest, balanced nutrition |\n| **Lordosis** (low back pain) | Caused by shifting center of gravity; pelvic tilts, supportive shoes |\n| **Leukorrhea** | Increased vaginal discharge \u2014 **normal** during pregnancy |\n| **Urinary frequency** | Normal in **1st and 3rd trimesters** (uterine pressure on bladder) |\n\n### Key Pregnancy Tests \u2b50\n| Test | What It Detects | When |\n|------|----------------|------|\n| **AFP (alpha-fetoprotein)** | **Neural tube defects** (elevated) / Down syndrome (low) | 2nd trimester (part of quad screen) |\n| **Amniocentesis** | Genetic disorders, lung maturity | US-guided to **avoid fetus and placenta** |\n| **GBS culture** | Group B Strep colonization | **35-37 weeks** |\n| **Glucose challenge** | Gestational diabetes | **24-28 weeks** |\n\n### Key Medications in Pregnancy \u2b50\n| Medication | Use | Key Nursing Points |\n|-----------|-----|-------------------|\n| **RhoGAM** | Rh incompatibility prevention | Given at 28 wk + within 72 hrs postpartum if baby Rh+ |\n| **Magnesium sulfate** | Seizure prevention (preeclampsia) + tocolytic | **Monitor respiratory rate** (hold if RR <12); check DTRs; antidote = **calcium gluconate** |\n| **Terbutaline** | Tocolytic (stops preterm contractions) | Side effects: **tachycardia, tremors, hyperglycemia, hypokalemia**; monitor FHR and maternal HR |\n| **Betamethasone** | Fetal lung maturity | Give **48 hrs before** anticipated preterm delivery; 2 doses 24 hrs apart |\n| **Rubella vaccine** | MMR \u2014 prevent rubella | **NEVER during pregnancy** (live vaccine); give **after delivery** |\n| **Ferrous sulfate** | Iron supplementation | Take with **OJ** (vitamin C); avoid milk/antacids; causes dark stools |\n\n### Quickening & Smoking\n- **Quickening**: first fetal movement felt by mother at **4-5 months** (16-20 weeks)\n- **Smoking**: increases risk of **preterm birth** and **low birth weight**\n\n### FDA Drug Categories in Pregnancy\n**A** (safe) \u2192 **B** \u2192 **C** \u2192 **D** (evidence of risk) \u2192 **X** (contraindicated)\n\n---\n\n## \u26a0\ufe0f HIGH-RISK PREGNANCY (Ch. 5) \u2014 Key Concepts\n\n### Danger Signs in Pregnancy \u2014 REPORT IMMEDIATELY\n- Sudden gush of fluid, vaginal bleeding, abdominal pain\n- Persistent vomiting, epigastric pain\n- Facial/hand edema, severe headache, blurred vision\n- Chills/fever >100.4\u00b0F, dysuria or \u2193 urine output\n\n### Hyperemesis Gravidarum\nExcessive N/V \u2192 dehydration \u2192 \u2193 placental perfusion \u2192 >5% weight loss, electrolyte imbalance, ketonuria\n\n### Hyperemesis vs. Normal Morning Sickness\n| Normal N/V | Hyperemesis Gravidarum |\n|-----------|----------------------|\n| Mild, manageable | Excessive, persistent |\n| No weight loss | **>5% weight loss** |\n| Adequate hydration | Dehydration, ketonuria, electrolyte imbalance |\n\n### Types of Miscarriage/Abortion\n| Type | Description |\n|------|------------|\n| **Threatened** | Bleeding but cervix closed; pregnancy may continue |\n| **Inevitable** | Cervix dilating; pregnancy cannot be saved |\n| **Incomplete** | Some tissue passed, some retained |\n| **Complete** | All products of conception expelled |\n| **Missed** | Fetus dies but is retained |\n\n> Post-miscarriage teaching: Report increased bleeding, no tampons, temp q8h x 3 days, report fever \u2265100.4\u00b0F, no sex until cleared\n\n### Ectopic Pregnancy\nImplantation outside uterus (usually fallopian tube). **Rupture = emergency** \u2192 sharp pain, shoulder pain, shock signs. Tx: methotrexate or surgery.\n\n### Hydatidiform Mole (Molar Pregnancy)\n- Grape-like vesicles, \"snowstorm\" on ultrasound, no FHTs\n- Very high hCG, rapid uterine growth, early preeclampsia signs\n- Follow hCG for **1 year** after evacuation (choriocarcinoma risk)\n\n### Placenta Previa vs. Abruption\n\n| | Previa | Abruption |\n|---|-------|-----------|\n| **Bleeding** | Painless, bright red | Painful, dark red |\n| **Uterus** | Soft, relaxed | Firm, board-like |\n| **Location** | Placenta covers cervix | Placenta separates from wall |\n| **Assoc. with** | Prior C-sections | Cocaine, HTN, preeclampsia |\n\n### Preeclampsia \u2b50\n**Triad**: Hypertension + Edema + Proteinuria (after 20 weeks)\n- Risk factors: G1, obesity, age <19 or >35, multiples, chronic HTN, DM\n- **HELLP** = Hemolysis, Elevated Liver enzymes, Low Platelets\n- Tx: **Magnesium sulfate** (seizure prevention), antihypertensives (labetalol)\n- **Cure = DELIVERY**\n\n### Gestational Diabetes (GDM)\n- Screen 24-28 weeks (glucose challenge)\n- Risks: macrosomia, neonatal hypoglycemia, delayed lung maturation\n- Tx: diet, exercise, insulin if needed\n- True GDM \u2192 glucose normalizes by 6 weeks postpartum\n\n### Rh Incompatibility\n- Problem: **Rh\u2212 mom + Rh+ baby** \u2192 mom makes antibodies \u2192 destroys fetal RBCs (**erythroblastosis fetalis**)\n- Prevention: **RhoGAM** at 28 weeks and within 72 hours after delivery\n\n### TORCH Infections\n| Letter | Infection | Key Points |\n|--------|----------|------------|\n| **T** | Toxoplasmosis | Cat feces, raw meat; neurologic damage |\n| **O** | Other (syphilis, Hep B, GBS) | GBS: culture 35-37wk, IV abx in labor |\n| **R** | Rubella | Cataracts, deafness, cardiac defects, IUGR; vaccine BEFORE pregnancy |\n| **C** | CMV | Most common congenital viral infection |\n| **H** | Herpes | C-section if active lesions at delivery |\n\n### DIC (Disseminated Intravascular Coagulation)\n- Clot formation AND clot destruction co-occur \u2192 depletes clotting factors\n- Signs: bleeding from nose, gums, incisions, venipuncture sites; rising uterine size; tender hard uterus\n- **Life-threatening emergency** \u2192 clotting factors + blood products\n\n### Hypovolemic Shock Signs \u2b50\n- Fetal heart rate changes\n- Rising weak pulse (**tachycardia = earliest sign**)\n- Rising respiratory rate, shallow respirations\n- **Falling BP** (late sign)\n- \u2193 Urine output (<30 mL/hr), pale/cold/clammy skin, faintness, thirst\n\n### Anemias in Pregnancy\n| Type | Key Facts |\n|------|----------|\n| **Iron-deficiency** | Most common; fatigue, pallor, tachycardia; Tx: oral iron x 3 months after correction |\n| **Folic acid deficiency** | Tx: 1 mg/day (higher if prior NTD baby) |\n| **Sickle cell** | Autosomal recessive; pregnancy can trigger crisis \u2192 vessel occlusion \u2192 preterm birth, IUGR; O2 + fluids throughout labor |\n\n### Heart Disease in Pregnancy\n- Blood volume \u2191 40-50% \u2192 can overwhelm compromised heart \u2192 **CHF**\n- Increased clotting factors \u2192 **thrombosis risk**\n- Fetus suffers from reduced placental blood flow\n\n### UTIs in Pregnancy\n- Increased UTI risk due to urinary stasis and hormonal changes\n- **Pyelonephritis**: high fever, chills, flank pain, N/V \u2192 can trigger preterm labor\n- Tx: antibiotics; encourage fluids, complete full course\n\n### Harmful Substances in Pregnancy\nAlcohol, cocaine, marijuana, tobacco, heroin, amphetamines, certain anticoagulants\n> \u26a0\ufe0f See Table 5.9 in textbook for complete substance/effect list\n\n---\n\n*\ud83d\udcdd Good luck on your exam tomorrow! Focus on the \u2b50 starred topics \u2014 those are the highest-yield.*\n";
window.studyGuideContent["ob_comprehensive"] = "# Comprehensive Study Guide: Fetal Development, Prenatal Care & Pregnancy Adaptations\n### OB/Maternity Chapters 3, 4 & 5\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 3: Fetal Development\n\n### 1. Cell Biology Foundations\n\nBefore a baby can develop, you need to understand how cells work at the most basic level.\n\n**Mitosis vs. Meiosis**\n- **Mitosis** is how the body grows and repairs itself. One cell splits into two identical copies, each with the full set of 46 chromosomes (23 pairs). This is what happens in ordinary tissue growth \u2014 skin healing, organs growing, etc.\n- **Meiosis** is special cell division that only happens in the sex cells (sperm and ova). It reduces the chromosome count in half, to 23. This way, when a sperm (23 chromosomes) fertilizes an ovum (23 chromosomes), the resulting zygote has the normal 46.\n\n**Why it matters clinically**: Errors during meiosis cause chromosomal disorders. Trisomy 21 (Down syndrome) occurs when chromosome 21 fails to separate properly, giving the offspring three copies instead of two. Turner syndrome involves a missing or incomplete X chromosome.\n\n### 2. Gametogenesis and Fertilization\n\n**Gametogenesis** is the process of forming sex cells:\n- In males: **spermatogenesis** (continuous from puberty)\n- In females: **oogenesis** (begins at ovulation, completes at fertilization). One oocyte matures per menstrual cycle.\n\n**The Moment of Fertilization**:\n- Occurs in the **outer third (ampulla) of the fallopian tube**\n- Sperm can reach the fallopian tubes within **5 minutes** of ejaculation\n- Sperm remain viable for **up to 5 days**\n- The ovum is viable for only **24 hours** after release\n- Sex is determined at fertilization: sperm carrying an X chromosome \u2192 XX (female), Y chromosome \u2192 XY (male)\n- The union of sperm and ovum creates a **zygote** \u2014 the very first cell of a new organism\n\n**Inheritance**:\n- Genes carry dominant and recessive traits\n- If one parent carries a dominant trait, ~50% of offspring will show it\n- If both parents carry a recessive gene, there is a 25% chance a child will express that recessive trait\n\n### 3. From Fertilization to Implantation\n\nThis journey takes approximately **one week**:\n\n1. **Zygote** \u2014 the single fertilized cell begins rapid mitotic division (called **cleavage**)\n2. **Morula** \u2014 by about day 3, the dividing cells form a solid ball of 16-32 cells that enters the uterus\n3. **Blastocyst** \u2014 the morula develops a cavity and two cell layers (inner and outer). It floats in the uterus for 2-4 more days\n4. **Implantation** \u2014 the blastocyst burrows into the endometrium, usually in the **upper portion of the posterior uterine wall**\n\nOnce implantation occurs, the endometrium is called the **decidua** (because of greater vascularization). The area directly under the blastocyst is called the **decidua basalis**, which becomes the **maternal part of the placenta**.\n\n**Key point**: During the week between fertilization and implantation, all cells within the zygote are identical. After implantation, cells begin to **differentiate** and develop specialized functions. Four structures appear: the chorion, amnion, yolk sac, and primary germ layers.\n\n### 4. The Chorion and Amnion\n\nThese two membranes are critical structures:\n- **Chorion**: develops from the outer layer (trophoblast); envelops the amnion, embryo, and yolk sac. Eventually forms the **fetal portion of the placenta**.\n- **Amnion**: thin inner membrane that directly envelops the embryo\n- Together they form the **amniotic sac**\n\n**Amniotic fluid volume** increases throughout pregnancy:\n- ~30 mL at 10 weeks\n- ~350 mL at 20 weeks\n- ~**1000 mL at 37 weeks**\n\nToo little fluid = **oligohydramnios**. Too much = **polyhydramnios** (hydramnios).\n\n**Functions of amniotic fluid**: cushions the fetus, maintains temperature, allows movement for musculoskeletal development, prevents adhesions.\n\n### 5. The Three Germ Layers\n\nAfter implantation, three primary germ layers form that give rise to ALL body tissues:\n\n**Ectoderm** (outer layer):\n- Outer layer of skin, oil glands, hair follicles\n- Nails and hair\n- External sense organs (eyes, ears)\n- Mucous membrane of mouth and anus\n- **The entire nervous system**\n\n**Mesoderm** (middle layer):\n- True skin (dermis)\n- Skeleton, bone and cartilage\n- Connective tissue\n- Muscles\n- Blood and blood vessels\n- Kidneys and gonads\n\n**Endoderm** (inner layer):\n- Lining of trachea, pharynx, and bronchi\n- Lining of the digestive tract\n- Lining of bladder and urethra\n\n**Memory trick**: Ecto = Exterior (skin + nerves). Meso = Middle/Muscle. Endo = Internal linings.\n\n### 6. Embryonic and Fetal Milestones\n\n- By the end of **week 8**: ALL body systems are formed and functioning in a simple way. The embryo has a distinct human appearance, the tail has disappeared, sex organs are forming. Crown-rump length is ~30mm, weight ~6 grams. The embryo now enters the **fetal period**.\n- **20 weeks**: **age of viability** (per textbook) \u2014 the fetus could theoretically survive outside the uterus, though clinically viability is closer to 22-24 weeks. Fewer than 40% of infants born at 23-25 weeks survive.\n- **37 weeks**: considered term for obstetrical purposes\n- **39-40 weeks 6 days**: full term\n\n### 7. The Placenta\n\nThe placenta is a **temporary organ** that serves as the site for fetal respiration, nutrition, and excretion. It also acts as an **endocrine gland**, producing **four hormones**:\n\n| Hormone | Key Functions |\n|---------|--------------|\n| **Progesterone** | Maintains uterine lining for implantation; reduces uterine contractions (prevents spontaneous abortion); prepares breast glands for lactation; stimulates fetal testes to produce testosterone |\n| **Estrogen** | Stimulates uterine growth; increases blood flow to uterine vessels; stimulates breast duct development; increases skin pigmentation; vascular changes in skin and mucous membranes |\n| **hCG (human chorionic gonadotropin)** | Signals that conception has occurred; causes corpus luteum to persist and continue producing estrogen and progesterone; detectable in blood 7-9 days after fertilization (this is what pregnancy tests detect) |\n| **hPL (human placental lactogen)** | Decreases maternal insulin sensitivity and glucose utilization, making more glucose available to the fetus for growth (\"diabetogenic effect\"); also called human chorionic somatomammotropin |\n\n**What the placenta does NOT do**: The thin placental membrane allows exchange of oxygen and waste products without mixing maternal and fetal blood. However, it is **not a barrier** \u2014 most substances ingested by the mother (drugs, nicotine, viral agents) can cross to the fetus.\n\n### 8. The Umbilical Cord\n\n- Contains **2 arteries and 1 vein** (remember: \"AVA\" \u2014 Artery, Vein, Artery)\n- **Arteries** carry deoxygenated blood and waste products **away** from the fetus to the placenta\n- **Vein** carries oxygenated, nutrient-rich blood **to** the fetus\n- Covered by **Wharton jelly** \u2014 a gelatinous substance that cushions the vessels and keeps them separated, preventing compression\n- Normal length: **55 cm (22 inches)**\n- Usually protrudes near the center of the placenta\n\n### 9. Fetal Circulation and the Three Shunts\n\nFetal circulation is unique because the lungs and liver are not yet fully functional. Three shunts redirect blood flow:\n\n**1. Ductus Venosus** \u2014 diverts some blood **away from the liver** as it returns from the placenta via the umbilical vein\n- Closes functionally when the cord is cut\n- Closes permanently in about 1 week \u2192 becomes a ligament\n\n**2. Foramen Ovale** \u2014 an opening between the right and left atria that diverts most blood from the **right atrium directly to the left atrium**, bypassing the lungs\n- Closes functionally within **2 hours** after birth\n- Closes permanently by about **3 months** of age\n\n**3. Ductus Arteriosus** \u2014 diverts most blood from the **pulmonary artery into the aorta**, also bypassing the lungs\n- Closes functionally within **15 hours** after birth\n- Closes permanently in about **3 weeks** \u2192 becomes a ligament\n- Failure to close = **patent ductus arteriosus (PDA)**, a congenital heart defect\n\n**After birth**: The baby's first breath expands the lungs, dramatically increasing pulmonary blood flow. This triggers closure of all three shunts. The ductus arteriosus and ductus venosus become ligaments after permanent closure.\n\n### 10. Twins and Multifetal Pregnancy\n\n**Monozygotic (identical) twins**: develop from a single fertilized ovum that splits at the end of the first week. They share a common chorion and placenta with some common vessels. Each has its own amnion.\n\n**Dizygotic (fraternal) twins**: develop from two separate ova fertilized by two separate sperm. They always have two amnions, two chorions, and two placentas (though chorions/placentas may fuse). They are genetically as similar as any two siblings. Tend to run in families.\n\n**Conjoined twins**: occur when the embryonic disc does not divide completely. They form within a single amnion and are named according to the regions that are joined.\n\n### 11. Teratogens and Impaired Development\n\n**Teratogens** are agents that cause damage to growing embryonic cells, potentially resulting in malformation. Examples include:\n- Certain prescribed medications\n- Alcohol, tobacco, cocaine, heroin\n- Maternal undernutrition\n- Infections (TORCH)\n- Environmental chemicals and radiation\n\n**Undernutrition in utero** can cause permanent changes in fetal structure, physiology, and metabolism, potentially leading to chronic conditions later in life. This is why maternal nutrition during pregnancy is so critical.\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 4: Prenatal Care and Adaptations to Pregnancy\n\n### 1. Obstetric Terminology\n\n| Term | Definition |\n|------|-----------|\n| **Gravida** | Total number of pregnancies (including current) |\n| **Para** | Number of pregnancies carried to \u226520 weeks (regardless of whether infant was born alive or still) |\n| **Nulligravida** | A woman who has never been pregnant |\n| **Primigravida** | A woman in her first pregnancy |\n| **Multigravida** | A woman who has been pregnant more than once |\n| **Nullipara** | A woman who has never given birth past 20 weeks |\n| **Primipara** | A woman who has given birth once past 20 weeks |\n| **Multipara** | A woman who has given birth 2 or more times past 20 weeks |\n| **GTPAL** | Gravida, Term births, Preterm births, Abortions/miscarriages, Living children |\n| **LNMP/LMP** | Last normal menstrual period |\n| **Quickening** | First fetal movements felt by the mother |\n| **Lightening** | When the fetus drops into the pelvis near term |\n| **Postpartum** | Period after delivery |\n\n### 2. Phases and Goals of Prenatal Care\n\nPregnancy has three phases:\n- **Antepartum** (before delivery)\n- **Intrapartum** (during labor and delivery)\n- **Postpartum** (after delivery)\n\n**Preconceptual care**: Care provided when planning a pregnancy. Identifies current medical issues, medications, and lifestyle concerns to optimize health before conception.\n\n**Major goals of prenatal care**:\n1. Ensure a healthy outcome for mother and baby\n2. Identify risk factors early\n3. Provide education and support\n4. Monitor fetal growth and development\n5. Prevent or manage complications\n\n### 3. Determining the Due Date\n\n**N\u00e4gele's Rule**:\n1. Identify the first day of the last menstrual period (LMP)\n2. Count backward 3 months\n3. Add 7 days\n4. Update the year if applicable\n\n**Example**: LMP = May 5, 2025 \u2192 Back 3 months = February 5 \u2192 Add 7 days = **February 12, 2026**\n\nAverage pregnancy = **40 weeks (280 days)** from the first day of LMP, \u00b12 weeks.\n\n**Trimesters**:\n- First: weeks 1-12\n- Second: weeks 13-27\n- Third: weeks 28-40\n\n### 4. Signs of Pregnancy\n\n**Presumptive signs** (subjective \u2014 felt by the woman, could have other causes):\n- Amenorrhea (missed period)\n- Nausea and vomiting (\"morning sickness\")\n- Breast tenderness and changes\n- Urinary frequency\n- Fatigue and drowsiness\n- Quickening (fetal movement felt by mother, ~16-20 weeks)\n- Deepening skin pigmentation\n\n**Probable signs** (objective \u2014 detected by examiner, but still not 100% proof):\n- **Goodell sign**: softening of the cervix\n- **Chadwick sign**: purplish/bluish color of the cervix and vagina (increased blood supply)\n- **Hegar sign**: softening of the lower uterine segment\n- **McDonald sign**: ease of flexing the uterus on the cervix\n- Abdominal enlargement\n- Braxton Hicks contractions (irregular, painless \"practice\" contractions)\n- Ballottement (rebounding of fetus when tapped through abdomen)\n- Abdominal striae (stretch marks)\n- **Positive pregnancy test** (detects hCG \u2014 still only \"probable\" because rare conditions like molar pregnancy can also elevate hCG)\n\n**Positive signs** (definitive \u2014 only explained by pregnancy):\n- Fetal heartbeat detected by examiner (Doppler ~10-12 weeks, fetoscope ~18-20 weeks)\n- Fetal movements felt by examiner (not mother)\n- Visualization of fetus on ultrasound\n\n### 5. Prenatal Testing by Trimester\n\n**First Trimester**:\n- Blood type and Rh factor with antibody screen\n- CBC (complete blood count)\n- RPR/VDRL (syphilis screening)\n- Rubella titer (immunity check)\n- TB screening (PPD or QuantiFERON-TB Gold)\n- Hepatitis B surface antigen\n- HIV screening\n- Urinalysis and urine culture\n- Pap test\n- Vaginal cultures for chlamydia and gonorrhea\n- Hemoglobin A1C\n- First trimester genetic screening (NIPT, CF/genetic markers)\n- Optional: hemoglobin electrophoresis (sickle cell), transvaginal ultrasound\n\n**Second Trimester**:\n- Quad screen (AFP, hCG, estriol, inhibin-A) \u2014 screens for Down syndrome, neural tube defects\n- Anatomy ultrasound (~18-22 weeks)\n- Glucose challenge test for gestational diabetes screening (**24-28 weeks**)\n\n**Third Trimester**:\n- Real-time ultrasound and Doppler blood flow\n- **GBS (Group B Strep) culture** at **35-37 weeks**\n- Cervical fetal fibronectin (preterm labor risk)\n- Possible repeat STI/HIV testing, CBC, RPR\n- NST (non-stress test), BPP (biophysical profile), AFI (amniotic fluid index)\n\n### 6. Routine Assessments at Every Prenatal Visit\n\nAt each visit, the nurse should assess:\n1. **Risk factors** (known and newly identified)\n2. **Vital signs and weight** (is weight gain normal?)\n3. **Urinalysis** (checking for glucose and protein)\n4. **Fundal height** (to assess fetal growth \u2014 should roughly equal gestational age in cm from 20-36 weeks)\n5. **Leopold maneuvers** (assessing fetal presentation and position in late pregnancy)\n6. **Fetal heart rate** (normal: 110-160 bpm)\n7. **Nutrition assessment** (adequate intake of key nutrients?)\n8. **Discomforts or problems** since last visit\n9. Any ER visits or hospitalizations\n\n### 7. Physiological Changes During Pregnancy\n\n**Uterine changes**: The uterus grows from ~60g to ~1000g. Blood supply increases dramatically.\n\n**Vaginal changes**: Increased blood supply, thickened mucosa, more prominent rugae. Secretions increase. pH becomes more acidic (protective against some infections but increases risk for yeast infections).\n\n**Breast changes**: Hormone-induced changes begin early. High estrogen and progesterone prepare for lactation. Areolae darken, sebaceous glands become prominent, colostrum may be expressed in the last few months.\n\n**Cardiovascular changes**: Blood volume increases 40-50%. Heart rate increases. Cardiac output increases. Blood pressure may decrease slightly in second trimester.\n\n**Supine Hypotension Syndrome**: When a pregnant woman lies flat on her back, the heavy uterus compresses the **inferior vena cava**, reducing blood return to the heart. This causes a sudden drop in blood pressure, dizziness, and pallor.\n- **Nursing intervention: Turn the patient to her LEFT SIDE** (displaces the uterus off the vena cava)\n- This is especially important during fetal monitoring, labor, and anytime the patient is supine\n\n**Hematologic changes** \u2014 pregnancy blood values differ from non-pregnant:\n| Lab Value | Pregnant | Non-Pregnant |\n|-----------|----------|-------------|\n| Hemoglobin | 11-12 g/dL | 12-16 g/dL |\n| Hematocrit | 33-46% | 36-48% |\n| RBC | 4.5-6.5 million/mm3 | 3.8-5.1 million |\n| WBC | 5,000-15,000/mm3 | 5,000-10,000 |\n| Fibrinogen | 300-600 mg/dL | 200-400 |\n\nNote: The lower hemoglobin/hematocrit is called **physiologic anemia of pregnancy** \u2014 it occurs because plasma volume increases more than red blood cell volume.\n\n### 8. Nutrition in Pregnancy\n\nThere is a **high correlation between maternal diet and fetal health**. Four nutrients are especially critical:\n\n**Protein** (60 g/day): Needed for metabolism and growth/repair of maternal and fetal tissues. Best sources: meat, fish, poultry, dairy products.\n\n**Calcium** (1000 mg DRI): Essential for fetal skeletal development. Requires adequate Vitamin D for absorption. Sources: dairy, enriched cereals, legumes, nuts, dried fruits, broccoli, leafy greens, canned salmon/sardines.\n\n**Iron** (30 mg/day \u2014 double the non-pregnant requirement): Prevents iron-deficiency anemia. **Ferrous sulfate** should be taken with **orange juice or vitamin C** to enhance absorption. Do NOT take with milk, antacids, or calcium (they inhibit absorption). Side effects include dark/black stools and constipation.\n\n**Folic acid** (400 mcg pre-conception through early pregnancy, then 600-800 mcg/day): A water-soluble B vitamin that significantly reduces the incidence of **neural tube defects** (spina bifida, anencephaly). Should ideally be started before conception.\n\n**Important warnings**:\n- **Excess Vitamin A is teratogenic** \u2014 can cause fetal anomalies and cardiac defects\n- **Vitamin B6 (pyridoxine) and ginger** are recommended for pregnancy nausea\n- **PICA**: the craving and ingestion of non-food substances (clay, starch, raw flour, cracked ice). It can indicate nutritional deficiencies and may be harmful.\n\n**Normal weight gain**: Approximately 25-35 lbs for a woman with normal pre-pregnancy BMI.\n\n### 9. Exercise and Activity During Pregnancy\n\n**Safe exercises**: Walking, swimming, low-impact aerobics, yoga (modified)\n\n**Activities to avoid**:\n- Hot tubs and saunas (hyperthermia risk to fetus)\n- Scuba diving (decompression risk)\n- Contact sports, horseback riding, skiing, skydiving\n- Vigorous exercise during hot, humid weather\n- Exercises while lying flat on back (after first trimester)\n\n**Travel during pregnancy**:\n- Seatbelt use: Lap belt goes **under the belly**, snug across hips/pelvic bone. Shoulder strap between breasts, off to the side of the belly.\n- Take frequent breaks for stretching and bathroom\n- Stay hydrated\n- Avoid prolonged immobility (increased DVT risk) \u2014 compression socks and ROM exercises help\n\n### 10. Common Discomforts of Pregnancy\n\n| Discomfort | Cause | Nursing Interventions |\n|-----------|-------|----------------------|\n| **Nausea/vomiting** | Rising hCG and hormonal changes | Small, frequent meals; dry crackers before rising; avoid greasy/spicy foods; Vitamin B6 + ginger; avoid strong odors |\n| **Heartburn** | Progesterone relaxes esophageal sphincter + uterine pressure | Small, frequent meals; upright position after eating; avoid spicy/fatty foods; antacids if provider-approved |\n| **Constipation** | Progesterone slows peristalsis + iron supplements | Increase fluids and fiber; regular exercise; stool softeners if needed |\n| **Urinary frequency** | Uterine pressure on bladder (1st and 3rd trimesters) | Normal; report burning or pain (UTI signs); Kegel exercises |\n| **Leg cramps** | Pressure on nerves, calcium/phosphorus imbalance | Dorsiflex the foot (point toes up); calcium and magnesium supplementation; avoid pointing toes |\n| **Fatigue** | Hormonal changes, increased metabolic demands | Rest periods; balanced nutrition; iron supplementation if anemic |\n| **Back pain** | Postural changes, shifting center of gravity | Good body mechanics; pelvic tilt exercises; supportive shoes; avoid high heels |\n\n### Additional Clinical Details from Instructor Review\n\n**Lordosis** \u2014 the increased lumbar spinal curve that develops as the center of gravity shifts forward with the growing uterus. This causes the characteristic low back pain of pregnancy. Management includes pelvic tilt exercises and supportive footwear.\n\n**Leukorrhea** \u2014 increased vaginal discharge during pregnancy is normal and results from hormonal changes and increased blood flow to the pelvic area.\n\n**Urinary frequency** \u2014 normal in both the first trimester (hormonal changes) and third trimester (uterine pressure on the bladder). Report burning or pain, which could indicate UTI.\n\n**Quickening** \u2014 first fetal movement felt by the mother at approximately 4-5 months (16-20 weeks). It is classified as a presumptive sign of pregnancy.\n\n**Fundal height landmarks**: At 20 weeks, the fundus reaches the umbilicus. From 20-36 weeks, fundal height in centimeters roughly equals gestational age in weeks. Immediately after delivery, the fundus is at the umbilicus and then descends 1-2 cm per day.\n\n**Smoking in pregnancy** significantly increases the risk of preterm birth, low birth weight, IUGR, and placental complications. Assess tobacco use at every visit and provide cessation resources.\n\n### Key Medications for Chapters 3-5\n\n**Magnesium sulfate**: Used for seizure prevention in preeclampsia and as a tocolytic. Critical nursing point: monitor respiratory rate and hold if RR drops below 12. Also assess deep tendon reflexes (absent DTRs = toxicity) and urine output (must be at least 30 mL/hr). Antidote: calcium gluconate.\n\n**Terbutaline**: Beta-adrenergic tocolytic. Side effects include tachycardia (maternal and fetal), tremors, hyperglycemia, and hypokalemia. Monitor maternal HR, FHR, blood glucose, and potassium.\n\n**Betamethasone**: Corticosteroid for fetal lung maturity. Give 48 hours before anticipated preterm delivery, two doses 24 hours apart.\n\n**Rubella vaccine** (MMR): Live vaccine \u2014 NEVER give during pregnancy. If prenatal rubella titer shows non-immunity, vaccinate after delivery. Avoid pregnancy for at least one month after vaccination.\n\n**Amniocentesis**: Performed under ultrasound guidance to avoid the fetus and placenta. Detects genetic disorders and assesses fetal lung maturity. Give RhoGAM afterward in Rh-negative mothers.\n\n**Alpha-fetoprotein (AFP)**: Second trimester screening. Elevated AFP suggests neural tube defects. Low AFP may indicate Down syndrome. Part of the quad screen (AFP, hCG, estriol, inhibin-A).\n\n### 11. Medications and Immunizations in Pregnancy\n\n**FDA Pregnancy Risk Categories**:\n- **Category A**: Controlled studies show no risk\n- **Category B**: No evidence of risk in humans\n- **Category C**: Risk cannot be ruled out\n- **Category D**: Positive evidence of risk, but benefits may outweigh\n- **Category X**: CONTRAINDICATED \u2014 proven fetal abnormalities\n\n**When in doubt, check FDA.gov**. The nurse should always verify pregnancy safety of any medication.\n\n**Immunizations**: Some vaccines are safe during pregnancy (e.g., flu shot, Tdap), while others are contraindicated (live vaccines like MMR, varicella). Rubella vaccine should be given **before** pregnancy if the woman is not immune.\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 5: Pregnancy Complications (Key Concepts)\n\n### Danger Signs in Pregnancy\nThese warrant **immediate** notification of the healthcare provider:\n- Sudden gush of fluid from vagina (possible ruptured membranes)\n- Vaginal bleeding\n- Abdominal pain\n- Persistent vomiting\n- Epigastric pain\n- Edema of face and hands\n- Severe, persistent headache\n- Blurred vision or dizziness\n- Chills with fever over 100.4\u00b0F\n- Painful urination or reduced urine output\n\n### Hyperemesis Gravidarum\n\nThis goes beyond normal morning sickness. Hyperemesis gravidarum involves excessive, persistent nausea and vomiting leading to dehydration (which impairs placental perfusion), weight loss greater than 5% of pre-pregnancy weight, electrolyte and acid-base imbalances, and ketonuria. Signs of dehydration include dry tongue and mucous membranes, decreased skin turgor, scant concentrated urine, and elevated hematocrit. Treatment involves IV fluid resuscitation, electrolyte replacement, antiemetics, and small frequent meals once tolerated.\n\n### Types of Miscarriage (Abortion)\n\nUnderstanding the different types is important for nursing assessment and communication:\n\n- **Threatened**: Vaginal bleeding but cervix remains closed. Pregnancy may continue. Nursing care includes bed rest and monitoring.\n- **Inevitable**: Cervix is dilating. Pregnancy cannot be saved. Bleeding and cramping increase.\n- **Incomplete**: Some products of conception expelled but tissue remains. May require D&C.\n- **Complete**: All products of conception expelled spontaneously. Bleeding subsides.\n- **Missed**: Fetus dies but is retained in the uterus. May require medical or surgical intervention.\n\nPost-miscarriage teaching: report increased bleeding, no tampons (infection risk), take temperature every 8 hours for 3 days, report fever 100.4 or above or foul-smelling discharge, avoid sexual activity until cleared. Use the term \"miscarriage\" rather than \"abortion\" with families. Provide emotional support, offer mementos if appropriate, chaplain referral, and support group information.\n\n### Bleeding Disorders\n\n**Ectopic pregnancy**: Implantation outside the uterus, most commonly in the fallopian tube. If tube ruptures: sudden severe lower abdominal pain, vaginal bleeding, signs of hypovolemic shock, and possible shoulder pain (from blood irritating the diaphragm). Treatment: observation if very early, methotrexate (inhibits cell division), or surgical removal. Priority is always to control bleeding.\n\n**Hydatidiform mole** (molar pregnancy): Abnormal trophoblastic growth creating sac-like vesicles resembling tiny grapes. Signs: vaginal bleeding, rapid uterine growth, no fetal heart activity, hyperemesis, unusually early preeclampsia, very high hCG, and \"snowstorm\" ultrasound pattern. Treatment is uterine evacuation. hCG must be followed until undetectable and monitored for at least 1 year due to choriocarcinoma risk.\n\n**Placenta previa vs. placental abruption**:\n| Feature | Placenta Previa | Placental Abruption |\n|---------|----------------|-------------------|\n| Location | Placenta implants low, covering cervix | Placenta separates from uterine wall |\n| Bleeding | **Painless**, bright red | **Painful**, dark red (may be concealed) |\n| Uterus | Soft, relaxed | Firm, board-like, tender |\n| Onset | Gradual | Can be sudden |\n| Risk factors | Prior C-sections, multiparity | Cocaine use, HTN, preeclampsia, trauma |\n| Key nursing point | No vaginal exams | Monitor for DIC |\n\n### Hypertensive Disorders of Pregnancy\n\n**Preeclampsia** (after 20 weeks gestation):\n- Classic triad: **Hypertension + Proteinuria + Edema**\n- Risk factors: first pregnancy (G1), obesity, family history, age <19 or >35, multiples, chronic HTN, DM, renal disease, autoimmune disease\n- Labs: hemoglobin, hematocrit, platelets, urine protein, serum creatinine, uric acid, liver transaminases\n- Treatment: magnesium sulfate (seizure prevention), labetalol (antihypertensive of choice), activity restriction, frequent fetal evaluation\n- **Birth is the cure for preeclampsia**\n\n**HELLP syndrome** \u2014 a severe form often seen in preeclamptic patients:\n- **H**emolysis\n- **E**levated **L**iver enzymes\n- **L**ow **P**latelets\n- Signs: RUQ pain, epigastric pain, nausea, vomiting, malaise\n- Usually requires ICU care, magnesium sulfate, and expedient delivery\n\n**Eclampsia**: Progression to seizures. Medical emergency.\n\n### Gestational Diabetes Mellitus (GDM)\n- Glucose intolerance with onset during pregnancy\n- Screening: glucose challenge test at **24-28 weeks**\n- Maternal effects of pregnancy hormones: increased insulin resistance and faster insulin breakdown\n- Maternal risks: spontaneous abortion, preeclampsia, preterm labor, polyhydramnios, infections, macrosomia complications, ketoacidosis\n- Fetal risks: congenital abnormalities, macrosomia (large baby), birth injury, delayed lung maturation, RDS, neonatal hypoglycemia, hypocalcemia, hyperbilirubinemia, polycythemia\n- Treatment: diet, exercise, blood glucose monitoring, insulin if needed\n- In true GDM, glucose usually returns to normal by **6 weeks postpartum**\n\n### Rh Incompatibility\nWhen an **Rh-negative mother** carries an **Rh-positive fetus**, fetal blood cells can enter the maternal circulation (especially at delivery). The mother's immune system creates antibodies against the Rh factor. In subsequent pregnancies with Rh+ fetuses, these antibodies cross the placenta and destroy fetal red blood cells (**erythroblastosis fetalis**).\n\nPrevention: **RhoGAM (Rh immunoglobulin)**\n- Given at **28 weeks** gestation\n- Given within **72 hours after delivery** of an Rh+ infant\n- Also given after any event where fetal-maternal blood mixing could occur (miscarriage, amniocentesis, trauma)\n\n### TORCH Infections\nThese infections are particularly dangerous during pregnancy:\n\n| | Infection | Transmission/Cause | Effects on Fetus/Newborn |\n|---|---------|-------------------|------------------------|\n| **T** | Toxoplasmosis | Cat feces, raw/undercooked meat | Low birth weight, enlarged liver/spleen, jaundice, anemia, eye inflammation, neurologic damage |\n| **O** | Other (Syphilis, Hep B, GBS, etc.) | Various; GBS diagnosed by vaginal/rectal culture at 35-37 weeks | GBS: sepsis, pneumonia, meningitis in newborn; prevented with IV antibiotics during labor |\n| **R** | Rubella | Viral; vaccine should be given BEFORE pregnancy | Microcephaly, intellectual disability, congenital cataracts, deafness, cardiac defects, IUGR |\n| **C** | Cytomegalovirus (CMV) | Most common congenital viral infection | Varies from asymptomatic to severe disability |\n| **H** | Herpes simplex | Direct contact; active lesions at delivery \u2192 C-section indicated | Neonatal herpes (potentially fatal) |\n\n### Other Key Conditions\n\n**Sickle cell disease in pregnancy**: Autosomal recessive disorder. Pregnancy can trigger a sickle cell crisis with massive RBC destruction and vessel occlusion. Risk to fetus: placental vessel occlusion leading to preterm birth, growth restriction, fetal demise. Oxygen and fluids given continuously throughout labor.\n\n**Iron-deficiency anemia**: Most common nutritional anemia in pregnancy. Symptoms: fatigue, pale skin/mucous membranes, SOB, tachycardia. Treatment: oral iron supplementation; continue 3 months after correction.\n\n**Folic acid deficiency anemia**: Treatment with 1 mg/day folic acid (higher dose if history of neural tube defect in previous child).\n\n**DIC (Disseminated Intravascular Coagulation)**: Life-threatening emergency where clot formation and destruction co-occur, depleting clotting factors. Signs: bleeding from nose, gums, incisions, venipuncture sites; increasing uterine size (blood accumulation); tender, hard uterus. Treatment: clotting factors and blood products.\n\n### Hypovolemic Shock\n\nHypovolemic shock is the major risk of hemorrhage during pregnancy. It interrupts blood flow to body cells, preventing oxygenation and nutrient delivery. The body initially compensates by increasing heart rate and respiratory rate to speed circulation of remaining blood. As shock progresses, blood flow to non-essential organs decreases and eventually stops.\n\nSigns and symptoms in order of progression: fetal heart rate changes (earliest fetal sign), rising weak pulse (tachycardia \u2014 the earliest maternal sign), rising respiratory rate with shallow irregular respirations, falling blood pressure (a late sign), decreased or absent urinary output (less than 30 mL/hr), pale cold clammy skin, faintness, and thirst. Nursing interventions focus on fluid resuscitation, blood replacement, and treating the underlying cause.\n\n### Heart Disease in Pregnancy\n\nThe dramatic cardiovascular changes of pregnancy (40-50% blood volume increase, elevated clotting factors) can overwhelm a compromised heart. If the heart cannot handle the increased workload, congestive heart failure results, and the fetus suffers from reduced placental blood flow. Increased clotting factors also raise the risk of thrombosis. Signs of CHF during pregnancy must be monitored carefully and managed with the obstetric and cardiology teams collaboratively.\n\n### Anemias in Pregnancy\n\n**Iron-deficiency anemia** is the most common nutritional anemia in pregnancy. Symptoms include easy fatigue, pale skin and mucous membranes, shortness of breath, pounding heart, and rapid pulse with severe anemia. Treatment involves oral iron supplementation, which should continue for approximately 3 months after the anemia has been corrected. Iron should be taken with vitamin C for better absorption.\n\n**Folic acid deficiency anemia** is treated with 1 mg/day of folic acid \u2014 over twice the preventive supplement dose. Women who have had a previous child with a neural tube defect may need an even higher dose.\n\n**Sickle cell disease** is an autosomal recessive disorder where abnormal hemoglobin causes red blood cells to become sickle-shaped during hypoxic or acidotic episodes. Pregnancy can trigger a sickle cell crisis with massive red blood cell destruction and vessel occlusion. Risk to the fetus includes placental vessel occlusion leading to preterm birth, growth restriction, and fetal demise. Oxygen and fluids should be given continuously throughout labor. Patients must be taught to prevent dehydration and avoid activities that cause hypoxia.\n\n### Urinary Tract Infections\n\nUTIs are more common during pregnancy due to hormonal changes that cause urinary stasis. Simple UTIs can progress to pyelonephritis, which presents with high fever, chills, flank pain or tenderness, nausea, and vomiting. Pyelonephritis is serious because it can trigger preterm labor. Treatment includes antibiotics (full course must be completed), increased fluid intake, and monitoring for preterm contractions.\n\n### Environmental Hazards and Substance Use\n\nMultiple substances are harmful to the developing fetus: alcohol (fetal alcohol spectrum disorders), cocaine (placental abruption, preterm birth), marijuana, tobacco (IUGR, low birth weight), heroin (neonatal abstinence syndrome), amphetamines, and certain anticoagulants. The nurse should assess for substance use in a nonjudgmental manner during prenatal care and provide education about the risks to fetal development.\n\n---\n\n*This guide covers the major testable content from Chapters 3, 4, and 5. For your Maternity & Newborn exam on Fetal Development, Prenatal Care, and Adaptations to Pregnancy, focus especially on the fetal shunts and their closure times, placental hormones, signs of pregnancy classification, Nagele's rule, prenatal lab timing, and the key differences between placenta previa and abruption.*\n";
window.studyGuideContent["cms_maternal_cheatsheet"] = "# ATI CMS Maternal & Newborn \u2014 Cheat Sheet\n### Comprehensive Quick Reference (All OB Chapters)\n\n---\n\n## 1. FETAL DEVELOPMENT (Ch. 3)\n\n### Fertilization & Early Development\n- Fertilization occurs in **outer third of fallopian tube**\n- Sperm viable **5 days**, ovum viable **24 hours**\n- Zygote \u2192 Morula (day 3) \u2192 Blastocyst \u2192 Implants (~day 7)\n- Implants in **upper posterior uterine wall**\n- Decidua basalis = maternal portion of placenta\n\n### Germ Layers\n| Layer | Structures |\n|-------|-----------|\n| **Ectoderm** | Skin, hair, nails, nervous system, sense organs |\n| **Mesoderm** | Skeleton, muscles, blood vessels, kidneys, gonads |\n| **Endoderm** | GI lining, trachea, bronchi, bladder, urethra |\n\n### Milestones\n- **8 weeks**: All systems formed \u2192 enters fetal period\n- **20 weeks**: Age of viability (textbook)\n- **37 weeks**: Term; **39-40 weeks**: Full term\n- Amniotic fluid: 30mL (10wk) \u2192 350mL (20wk) \u2192 **1000mL (37wk)**\n\n### Placental Hormones\n| Hormone | Function |\n|---------|----------|\n| **Progesterone** | Maintains lining, prevents contractions, preps breasts |\n| **Estrogen** | Uterine growth, blood flow, breast duct development |\n| **hCG** | Signals conception, maintains corpus luteum (detected by pregnancy tests) |\n| **hPL** | Decreases maternal insulin sensitivity \u2192 more glucose to fetus |\n\n### Umbilical Cord: **2 arteries** (waste away) + **1 vein** (O2 to fetus) + Wharton jelly\n\n### Three Fetal Shunts \u2b50\n| Shunt | Bypasses | Closes |\n|-------|---------|--------|\n| **Ductus venosus** | Liver | Cord cut (perm ~1 wk) |\n| **Foramen ovale** | Lungs (R\u2192L atrium) | **2 hrs** (perm ~3 mo) |\n| **Ductus arteriosus** | Lungs (PA\u2192aorta) | **15 hrs** (perm ~3 wk) |\n\n### Twins\n- **Monozygotic** = identical, 1 egg, shared chorion/placenta\n- **Dizygotic** = fraternal, 2 eggs, separate placentas\n\n---\n\n## 2. PRENATAL CARE & ADAPTATIONS (Ch. 4)\n\n### OB Terminology\n- **GTPAL**: Gravida, Term, Preterm, Abortions, Living\n- **Para** = births \u226520 weeks (alive or still)\n\n### EDD: Nagele's Rule \u2b50\n> **LMP \u2212 3 months + 7 days** (average pregnancy = 40 weeks/280 days)\n\n### Signs of Pregnancy\n| Presumptive | Probable | Positive |\n|------------|---------|---------|\n| Amenorrhea, N/V, fatigue | Goodell (cervix soft) | FHR heard by examiner |\n| Breast changes, quickening | Chadwick (purplish cervix) | Fetal movement felt by examiner |\n| Urinary frequency | Hegar (lower uterus soft) | Fetus on ultrasound |\n| Deepening pigmentation | +hCG test, Braxton Hicks | |\n\n### Prenatal Labs by Trimester\n- **1st**: Blood type/Rh, CBC, RPR, rubella, TB, HepB, HIV, UA, Pap, STI screen, NIPT\n- **2nd**: Quad screen, anatomy US, **GDM screen (24-28 wk)**\n- **3rd**: **GBS culture (35-37 wk)**, NST/BPP, fetal fibronectin\n\n### Four Key Nutrients\n| Nutrient | Amount | Why |\n|----------|--------|-----|\n| Protein | 60 g/day | Tissue growth/repair |\n| Calcium | 1000 mg | Fetal skeleton (needs Vit D) |\n| Iron | 30 mg/day | Prevents anemia |\n| Folic acid | 400-800 mcg | Prevents **neural tube defects** |\n\n> \u26a0\ufe0f Excess Vitamin A = teratogenic | B6 + ginger = for nausea | PICA = eating non-food items\n\n### Supine Hypotension \u2192 **Turn to LEFT SIDE** (IVC compression)\n\n### Weight gain: **25-35 lbs** (normal BMI)\n\n---\n\n## 3. PREGNANCY COMPLICATIONS (Ch. 5)\n\n### Danger Signs \u2014 REPORT IMMEDIATELY\nSudden fluid gush, vaginal bleeding, abdominal pain, persistent vomiting, epigastric pain, face/hand edema, severe headache, blurred vision, fever >100.4\u00b0F, dysuria\n\n### Placenta Previa vs. Abruption \u2b50\n| | Previa | Abruption |\n|--|--------|-----------|\n| Bleeding | **Painless**, bright red | **Painful**, dark |\n| Uterus | Soft | Firm, board-like |\n| Risk factors | Prior C-sections | Cocaine, HTN |\n| Key point | **No vaginal exams** | Monitor for DIC |\n\n### Preeclampsia \u2b50\n- **Triad**: HTN + Proteinuria + Edema (after 20 wk)\n- **HELLP**: Hemolysis, Elevated Liver enzymes, Low Platelets\n- Tx: **Magnesium sulfate** (seizures), labetalol (BP)\n- **Cure = DELIVERY**\n\n### GDM\n- Screen **24-28 weeks**; risks: macrosomia, neonatal hypoglycemia\n- True GDM \u2192 glucose normalizes by **6 weeks postpartum**\n\n### Rh Incompatibility\n- Rh\u2212 mom + Rh+ baby \u2192 **erythroblastosis fetalis**\n- **RhoGAM** at 28 wk + within 72 hrs after delivery\n\n### TORCH Infections\n**T**oxoplasmosis (cat feces) | **O**ther (syphilis, GBS, HepB) | **R**ubella (vaccine before pregnancy) | **C**MV | **H**erpes (C-section if active lesions)\n\n---\n\n## 4. LABOR & BIRTH (Ch. 6)\n\n### Four Ps: **Powers, Passage, Passenger, Psyche**\n\n### Signs of Labor\nBloody show, ROM, regular contractions, lightening, nesting, weight loss\n\n### True vs. False Labor\n- **True**: Regular, increasing intensity, cervical change, not stopped by position change\n- **False**: Irregular, no cervical change, stops with rest/position change\n\n### Cardinal Movements \u2b50\n**Descent \u2192 Engagement \u2192 Flexion \u2192 Internal Rotation \u2192 Extension \u2192 External Rotation \u2192 Expulsion**\n\n### Stages of Labor\n| Stage | What Happens | Duration |\n|-------|-------------|----------|\n| 1st | Dilation & effacement (0-10 cm) | 4-6 hrs |\n| 2nd | Expulsion of fetus | 30 min - 2 hrs |\n| 3rd | Placenta delivery | 5-30 min |\n| 4th | Recovery | 1-2 hrs |\n\n### FHR Monitoring \u2b50\n- Normal baseline: **110-160 bpm**\n- VEAL CHOP: **V**ariable = **C**ord compression | **E**arly = **H**ead compression | **A**ccelerations = **O**K | **L**ate = **P**lacental insufficiency\n- Reassuring: moderate variability, accelerations\n- Non-reassuring: late decels, variable decels, absent variability\n\n### Amniotic Fluid\n- Normal: clear, flecks of vernix, no odor\n- **Green** = meconium (fetal distress) | **Foul odor** = infection\n\n### Apgar Score (1 & 5 min): **H**eart rate, **R**espiratory effort, **M**uscle tone, **R**eflex response, **C**olor (7-10 normal)\n\n### Newborn Meds: **Erythromycin eye ointment** + **Vitamin K (AquaMEPHYTON)**\n\n### Placenta Delivery: \"Shiny Schulze\" (fetal side) vs \"Dirty Duncan\" (maternal side)\n\n---\n\n## 5. PAIN MANAGEMENT IN LABOR (Ch. 7)\n\n### Nonpharmacologic\n- **Methods**: Dick-Read, Bradley, Lamaze\n- **Techniques**: Effleurage, breathing, relaxation, counterpressure\n- **Advantages**: No harm to mother/fetus, no drug side effects, won't slow labor\n- **Gate control theory**: Touch/massage blocks pain signals\n\n### Hyperventilation Signs \u2b50\nDizziness, tingling hands/feet, numbness around nose/mouth, hand cramps\n> **Fix**: Slow breathing, breathe into cupped hands, moist washcloth, brief breath-hold\n\n### Pharmacologic\n- **Analgesic** = blocks pain | **Anesthetic** = blocks pain + motor\n- **Opioids**: Avoid within **1 hour** of birth (neonatal respiratory depression) \u2192 antidote: **naloxone**\n- Two patients medicated: **mother AND fetus**\n\n### Types of Anesthesia\n| Type | Use |\n|------|-----|\n| Local infiltration | Episiotomy/laceration repair |\n| Pudendal block | Perineal area |\n| **Epidural** | Most common for labor |\n| Spinal (subarachnoid) | Cesarean birth |\n| General | Emergency C-section only |\n\n- General anesthesia risk: **aspiration of gastric contents**\n- Pregnancy increases aspiration risk (sluggish GI + aortocaval compression)\n\n---\n\n## 6. LABOR COMPLICATIONS (Ch. 8)\n\n### Perineal Lacerations\n- 1st degree: superficial mucosa/skin\n- 2nd degree: deeper perineal tissues\n- 3rd degree: + anal sphincter\n- 4th degree: extends through rectal mucosa\n\n### Cesarean Birth Incisions\n- **Low transverse**: VBAC possible, least rupture risk\n- **Classic (vertical)**: highest rupture risk, rarely used\n\n### Obstetric Emergencies\n- **Prolapsed cord**: Knee-chest position, hand in to lift presenting part off cord, emergency C-section\n- **Amniotic fluid embolism**: Respiratory support, treat shock, replace coagulation factors \u2192 ICU\n- **Uterine rupture**: Emergency surgical intervention\n\n### Preterm Labor\n- Risk factors: prior preterm birth, infection, multiples, PROM, substance abuse\n- **Fetal fibronectin** test predicts preterm labor risk\n- Treatment: **tocolytics** (terbutaline, nifedipine, MgSO4) + **betamethasone** (lung maturity, give 48 hrs before delivery)\n- Tocolytic contraindications: preeclampsia, placenta previa, abruption, >37 wk, fetal demise\n\n### Bishop Score: \u22656 predicts successful labor induction\n\n---\n\n## 7. POSTPARTUM CARE (Ch. 9)\n\n### BUBBLE Assessment \u2b50\n- **B**reasts (soft vs engorged)\n- **U**terus (firmness, fundal height, location)\n- **B**ladder (distention)\n- **B**owels (gas, bowel sounds, stool)\n- **L**ochia (character, amount, color, odor)\n- **E**pisiotomy/perineum (REEDA: Redness, Edema, Ecchymosis, Discharge, Approximation)\n\n### Lochia Progression \u2b50\n| Type | Color | Duration |\n|------|-------|----------|\n| **Rubra** | Red (mostly blood) | Days 1-3 |\n| **Serosa** | Pink (blood + mucus) | Days 4-10 |\n| **Alba** | White/clear (mucus) | Days 10-21 |\n\n### Involution\n- Uterus descends **1-2 cm/day**; not palpable by **day 10**\n- Returns to pre-pregnant size by **5-6 weeks**\n- Boggy fundus = **uterine atony** \u2192 massage fundus\n\n### Perineum Care\n- Ice pack first **12-24 hours** \u2192 Sitz bath after 24 hours\n- REEDA assessment for healing\n\n### Breastfeeding\n- **Prolactin** = milk production | **Oxytocin** = let-down reflex\n- Colostrum (first days) \u2192 Transitional milk (7-10 days) \u2192 Mature milk (14 days)\n- **Foremilk** (first) vs **Hindmilk** (higher fat, satisfies hunger)\n- Feed every **2-3 hours** \u2192 8-10 wet diapers/day\n- Engorgement around **day 3** \u2014 keep feeding frequently\n- Contraindications: **HIV, HTLV 1 & 2**\n- Storage: room temp 3 hrs, fridge 3 days, freezer 3 months\n\n### Rubin's Phases: Taking-in (dependent) \u2192 Taking-hold (independent) \u2192 Letting-go (role adjustment)\n\n### Car Seat: Rear-facing in back seat until **age 2**, harness snug\n\n---\n\n## 8. POSTPARTUM COMPLICATIONS (Ch. 10)\n\n### Postpartum Hemorrhage \u2b50\n- Early: within **24 hours** | Late: 24 hrs to **6 weeks**\n- Defined as >500 mL (vaginal) or >1000 mL (C-section)\n- **4 T's**: Tone (atony), Trauma, Tissue (retained placenta), Thrombin (clotting)\n- **#1 cause: Uterine atony** \u2192 boggy fundus, heavy lochia\n- Tachycardia is **earliest sign** of hypovolemic shock\n- Tx: Fundal massage, empty bladder, oxytocin, methylergonovine (Methergine)\n\n### Subinvolution\n- Slower than expected uterine return to normal\n- Signs: fundal height > expected, persistent lochia rubra, pelvic pain\n- Tx: Methergine, antibiotics, D&C if needed\n\n### Thromboembolic Disorders\n- **SVT** \u2192 heat, elevation, analgesics\n- **DVT** \u2192 heparin/LMWH (Lovenox), leg elevation; confirm by ultrasound\n- **PE** \u2192 sudden chest pain, dyspnea, cough \u2192 ICU\n- Prevention: early ambulation, SCDs, avoid popliteal pressure\n\n### Infections\n- **Puerperal sepsis**: Fever \u2265100.4\u00b0F within first 10 days PP\n- **Endometritis**: Most common cause of PP fever\n- **Mastitis**: Breast infection \u2014 continue breastfeeding, antibiotics, warm compresses before feeding, ice after\n- Weaning during mastitis **worsens** symptoms\n\n### Mood Disorders\n| Type | Onset | Features |\n|------|-------|---------|\n| **Baby blues** | Days 1-10 | Tearfulness, mood swings, resolves spontaneously |\n| **PP Depression** | 2-4 weeks | Persistent sadness, inability to cope, guilt, sleep/appetite changes |\n| **PP Psychosis** | Variable | Impaired reality, hallucinations \u2014 psychiatric emergency |\n\n> Never assume \"baby blues\" \u2014 explore persistent feelings\n\n---\n\n## 9. THE TERM NEWBORN (Ch. 12)\n\n### Head Assessment\n- Normal circumference: **32-36 cm** (no more than 2 cm > chest)\n- **Fontanelles**: Flat = normal | Bulging = increased ICP | Depressed = dehydration\n- **Molding**: Overlapping skull bones (normal, resolves)\n- **Caput succedaneum**: Soft tissue swelling (crosses suture lines)\n- **Cephalohematoma**: Bleeding under periosteum (does NOT cross suture lines)\n\n### Vital Signs\n- Temp: **36.2-37.7\u00b0C** (97.1-99.8\u00b0F)\n- HR: 110-160 bpm | RR: 30-60\n\n### Thermoregulation \u2014 Four Heat Loss Mechanisms\n| Type | How | Prevention |\n|------|-----|-----------|\n| **Evaporation** | Wet skin | Dry immediately after birth |\n| **Conduction** | Cold surfaces | Warm blankets, skin-to-skin |\n| **Convection** | Air currents | Avoid drafts, keep warm room |\n| **Radiation** | Cold nearby objects | Keep away from cold walls/windows |\n\n### Newborn Reflexes\n- **Rooting**: Touch cheek \u2192 turns toward stimulus\n- **Sucking**: Object in mouth \u2192 sucks\n- **Moro (startle)**: Sudden noise \u2192 arms extend then flex\n- **Grasp**: Object in palm \u2192 grips\n\n### Stool Progression\n**Meconium** (dark green/black, sterile) \u2192 **Transitional** \u2192 **Breast-fed** (yellow, seedy) or **Formula-fed** (pale yellow, firmer)\n\n### Neonatal Hypoglycemia\n- Blood glucose < **45 mg/dL**\n- Risk: preterm, LGA/SGA, diabetic mother, cold stress\n- Signs: jitteriness, poor tone, poor suck, high-pitched cry, lethargy, seizures\n\n### Cord Care: Clean and dry, diaper below cord, report redness/odor, sponge bath until stump falls off\n\n### Infection Prevention: **Hand hygiene** is #1; immature immune system = slow response\n\n### Newborn Screening: Hearing screen before discharge, metabolic screening\n\n---\n\n*\u2b50 = Highest-yield topics for ATI CMS. Focus on the shunts, Nagele's rule, BUBBLE assessment, lochia stages, FHR patterns (VEAL CHOP), preeclampsia management, postpartum hemorrhage, and newborn thermoregulation.*\n";
window.studyGuideContent["cms_maternal_comprehensive"] = "# ATI CMS Maternal & Newborn \u2014 Comprehensive Study Guide\n### Full Clinical Walkthrough: Conception Through Postpartum & Newborn\n\n---\n\n## Part 1: Fetal Development (Ch. 3)\n\n### How Life Begins\n\n**Cell division** underpins everything. Mitosis produces identical copies of body cells (46 chromosomes each). Meiosis is the special division used only for sex cells \u2014 it cuts the chromosome count in half to 23. When a sperm (23) meets an ovum (23), the resulting zygote has the full 46 again. Errors during meiosis cause chromosomal conditions like Trisomy 21 (Down syndrome \u2014 three copies of chromosome 21) and Turner syndrome (missing X chromosome).\n\n**Fertilization** happens in the outer third (ampulla) of the fallopian tube. Sperm can arrive there within 5 minutes of ejaculation and remain viable for up to 5 days. The ovum, however, only lives about 24 hours after release. Sex is determined at fertilization \u2014 an X-carrying sperm produces a female (XX), a Y-carrying sperm produces a male (XY).\n\n### The Journey to Implantation (About One Week)\n\nThe fertilized zygote undergoes rapid division (cleavage) as it travels through the fallopian tube. By day 3 it forms a solid ball of 16-32 cells called a **morula**, which enters the uterus. It floats there for 2-4 more days, developing into a **blastocyst** with inner and outer cell layers. Around day 7, it burrows into the endometrium \u2014 usually in the upper posterior uterine wall. This is **implantation**.\n\nAfter implantation, the endometrium is called the **decidua** (enriched with blood vessels). The area directly under the implanted blastocyst \u2014 the **decidua basalis** \u2014 becomes the maternal portion of the placenta. The cells begin to differentiate, forming the chorion, amnion, yolk sac, and three primary germ layers.\n\n### Germ Layers \u2014 The Blueprint for Every Body System\n\n- **Ectoderm** (outer): skin, hair, nails, nervous system, sense organs, mouth and anus lining. Think \"Ecto = Exterior.\"\n- **Mesoderm** (middle): skeleton, muscles, blood vessels, kidneys, gonads, connective tissue. Think \"Meso = Muscle.\"\n- **Endoderm** (inner): lining of the trachea, bronchi, digestive tract, bladder, urethra. Think \"Endo = Internal linings.\"\n\n### Key Developmental Milestones\n\nBy the end of **week 8**, all body systems are formed and functioning simply. The embryo looks distinctly human and enters the **fetal period**. The **age of viability** (when a fetus could potentially survive outside the uterus) is 20 weeks per textbook, though clinical viability is closer to 22-24 weeks \u2014 and fewer than 40% of infants born at 23-25 weeks survive. **Full term** is 39-40 weeks.\n\n**Amniotic fluid** volume increases steadily: about 30 mL at 10 weeks, 350 mL at 20 weeks, and 1000 mL at 37 weeks. Too little is oligohydramnios; too much is polyhydramnios. The fluid cushions the fetus, maintains temperature, allows movement, and prevents adhesions.\n\n### The Placenta as an Endocrine Organ\n\nThe placenta is temporary but critical \u2014 it handles fetal respiration, nutrition, and waste removal, and produces four hormones:\n\n**Progesterone** maintains the uterine lining for implantation, reduces contractions to prevent spontaneous abortion, prepares breast glands for lactation, and stimulates fetal testes to produce testosterone. **Estrogen** stimulates uterine growth, increases uterine blood flow, and develops breast ducts. **hCG** signals conception and keeps the corpus luteum producing estrogen and progesterone \u2014 it is detectable 7-9 days after fertilization and is what pregnancy tests detect. **hPL** (human placental lactogen) decreases maternal insulin sensitivity, shunting more glucose to the fetus \u2014 this \"diabetogenic\" effect explains why gestational diabetes develops.\n\nThe placenta allows exchange between maternal and fetal blood without mixing them. However, it is not a true barrier \u2014 most drugs, nicotine, alcohol, and viral agents cross to the fetus.\n\n### The Umbilical Cord\n\nThe cord contains **two arteries** (carrying deoxygenated blood and waste away from the fetus) and **one vein** (carrying oxygenated blood to the fetus). **Wharton jelly** cushions and separates the vessels, preventing compression. Normal length is about 55 cm.\n\n### Fetal Circulation: Three Shunts\n\nBecause the fetal lungs and liver are not yet functional, three shunts redirect blood:\n\n1. **Ductus venosus** \u2014 bypasses the liver. Closes when the cord is cut (permanently within about 1 week).\n2. **Foramen ovale** \u2014 bypasses the lungs by shunting blood from the right atrium directly to the left atrium. Closes functionally within 2 hours of birth (permanently by about 3 months). Failure to close = ASD.\n3. **Ductus arteriosus** \u2014 bypasses the lungs by shunting blood from the pulmonary artery to the aorta. Closes within 15 hours (permanently in about 3 weeks). Failure to close = patent ductus arteriosus (PDA).\n\nAfter birth, the baby's first breath dramatically increases pulmonary blood flow, triggering closure of all three shunts. The ductus arteriosus and ductus venosus eventually become ligaments.\n\n### Twins and Teratogens\n\n**Monozygotic** (identical) twins come from one fertilized ovum that splits \u2014 they share a chorion and placenta. **Dizygotic** (fraternal) twins come from two separate ova fertilized by two sperm \u2014 each has its own chorion and placenta (though they may fuse). Dizygotic twinning runs in families.\n\n**Teratogens** are agents that damage embryonic development: medications, alcohol, tobacco, cocaine, infections (TORCH), maternal malnutrition, and environmental exposures. The embryonic period (first 8 weeks) is when the fetus is most vulnerable.\n\n---\n\n## Part 2: Prenatal Care & Adaptations (Ch. 4)\n\n### Obstetric Terminology\n\nUnderstanding GTPAL is essential: **G**ravida (total pregnancies), **T**erm births, **P**reterm births, **A**bortions/miscarriages, **L**iving children. Para counts pregnancies carried to 20+ weeks regardless of whether the infant was born alive. A nullipara has never delivered past 20 weeks; a multipara has delivered 2+ times past 20 weeks.\n\n### Calculating the Due Date\n\n**Nagele's Rule**: Take the first day of the last menstrual period (LMP), count back 3 months, add 7 days, and update the year. Average pregnancy is 40 weeks (280 days) from LMP. Trimesters: first (weeks 1-12), second (13-27), third (28-40).\n\n### Signs of Pregnancy\n\n**Presumptive** signs are subjective and could have other causes: amenorrhea, nausea, breast tenderness, fatigue, urinary frequency, quickening (mother feels fetal movement), and darkening pigmentation. **Probable** signs are objective but not definitive: Goodell sign (cervical softening), Chadwick sign (purplish cervix), Hegar sign (lower uterine softening), positive pregnancy test (hCG), Braxton Hicks contractions, ballottement, and abdominal enlargement. **Positive** signs are definitive: fetal heartbeat detected by the examiner, fetal movement felt by the examiner, and fetus visualized on ultrasound.\n\n### Prenatal Testing Timeline\n\nFirst trimester labs cast a wide net: blood type and Rh factor, antibody screen, CBC, syphilis (RPR), rubella titer, TB screening, Hepatitis B, HIV, urinalysis/culture, Pap test, chlamydia/gonorrhea cultures, HbA1C, and genetic screening (NIPT). Second trimester adds the quad screen (for Down syndrome and neural tube defects), anatomy ultrasound, and the glucose challenge test for gestational diabetes at 24-28 weeks. Third trimester includes GBS culture at 35-37 weeks, possible repeat STI/HIV testing, and fetal surveillance (NST, BPP, AFI).\n\nAt every visit: vital signs and weight, urinalysis for glucose and protein, fundal height (should roughly equal gestational age in cm from 20-36 weeks), FHR (normal 110-160), Leopold maneuvers in late pregnancy, nutrition assessment, and screening for discomforts or danger signs.\n\n### Nutrition in Pregnancy\n\nFour nutrients are critical. **Protein** (60 g/day) supports tissue growth. **Calcium** (1000 mg) builds the fetal skeleton and requires adequate Vitamin D for absorption. **Iron** (30 mg/day \u2014 double the non-pregnant need) prevents anemia. **Folic acid** (400-800 mcg) dramatically reduces neural tube defects and should ideally be started before conception.\n\nImportant warnings: excess Vitamin A is teratogenic (causes cardiac defects). Vitamin B6 and ginger help with pregnancy nausea. PICA \u2014 craving non-food substances like clay, starch, or ice \u2014 may indicate nutritional deficiency. Normal weight gain is approximately 25-35 pounds for a woman with normal pre-pregnancy BMI.\n\n### Pregnancy-Related Physiological Changes\n\nBlood volume increases 40-50%, heart rate increases, and cardiac output rises. The lower hemoglobin/hematocrit values seen in pregnancy reflect **physiologic anemia** \u2014 plasma volume expands faster than red blood cell production. WBC count also rises (up to 15,000 normally). Fibrinogen increases, creating a hypercoagulable state.\n\n**Supine hypotension syndrome** occurs when the heavy uterus compresses the inferior vena cava in the supine position, reducing venous return and causing hypotension and dizziness. The fix is simple: turn the patient to her **left side**.\n\n### Common Discomforts and Their Management\n\nNausea responds to small frequent meals, dry crackers before rising, and B6 plus ginger. Heartburn improves with upright positioning after meals and small portions. Constipation (worsened by progesterone and iron supplements) is managed with fluids, fiber, and exercise. Leg cramps are treated by dorsiflexing the foot. For travel, the lap belt goes under the belly across the hips; compression stockings and frequent breaks help prevent DVT.\n\n---\n\n## Part 3: Pregnancy Complications (Ch. 5)\n\n### Danger Signs That Require Immediate Reporting\n\nSudden gush of fluid, vaginal bleeding, abdominal pain, persistent vomiting, epigastric pain, edema of face and hands, severe headache, blurred vision, chills with fever over 100.4 degrees F, painful urination, or decreased urine output.\n\n### Bleeding Disorders\n\n**Ectopic pregnancy** \u2014 implantation outside the uterus (usually the fallopian tube). If it ruptures: sudden severe pain, vaginal bleeding, signs of shock, possible shoulder pain. Treatment is methotrexate or surgery. **Hydatidiform mole** \u2014 abnormal trophoblastic growth creating grape-like vesicles with a \"snowstorm\" ultrasound pattern and very high hCG. Follow hCG levels for at least 1 year after evacuation.\n\n**Placenta previa** presents with painless, bright red bleeding and a soft uterus \u2014 the placenta implants over the cervix. Key nursing point: no vaginal exams. **Placental abruption** presents with painful, dark red bleeding, a firm board-like uterus, and is associated with cocaine use, hypertension, and preeclampsia. Monitor for DIC.\n\n### Hypertensive Disorders\n\n**Preeclampsia** develops after 20 weeks with the classic triad of hypertension, proteinuria, and edema. Risk factors include first pregnancy, obesity, extremes of age, multiples, and chronic conditions. Labs to monitor: H&H, platelets, urine protein, creatinine, uric acid, and liver enzymes. **HELLP syndrome** (Hemolysis, Elevated Liver enzymes, Low Platelets) is a severe form with RUQ pain and nausea. Treatment centers on magnesium sulfate for seizure prevention and labetalol for blood pressure. The cure is delivery.\n\n### Gestational Diabetes\n\nPregnancy hormones increase insulin resistance and accelerate insulin breakdown. Screening occurs at 24-28 weeks via glucose challenge. Maternal risks include preeclampsia, preterm labor, polyhydramnios, and macrosomia complications. Fetal risks include congenital abnormalities, macrosomia, birth injury, delayed lung maturation, neonatal hypoglycemia, and hyperbilirubinemia. Treatment involves diet, exercise, glucose monitoring, and insulin if needed. In true GDM, glucose normalizes by 6 weeks postpartum.\n\n### Rh Incompatibility\n\nWhen an Rh-negative mother carries an Rh-positive fetus, fetal blood cells entering the maternal circulation trigger antibody production. In subsequent Rh-positive pregnancies, these antibodies destroy fetal red blood cells (erythroblastosis fetalis). Prevention: RhoGAM at 28 weeks and within 72 hours after delivery of an Rh-positive infant.\n\n### TORCH Infections\n\n**T**oxoplasmosis (cat feces, raw meat \u2014 causes neurologic damage), **O**ther (syphilis, Hep B, GBS \u2014 GBS cultured at 35-37 weeks, treated with IV antibiotics in labor), **R**ubella (cataracts, deafness, cardiac defects \u2014 vaccinate before pregnancy, never during), **C**MV (most common congenital viral infection), **H**erpes (C-section if active lesions at delivery).\n\n---\n\n## Part 4: Labor & Birth (Ch. 6)\n\n### The Four Ps\n\n**Powers** \u2014 uterine contractions (involuntary) and maternal pushing (voluntary). Contractions have three phases: increment (building), peak (acme), and decrement (letting up). They are assessed for frequency, duration, and intensity. **Passage** \u2014 the bony pelvis (true pelvis: inlet, midpelvis, outlet) and soft tissues. **Passenger** \u2014 the fetus and placenta. **Psyche** \u2014 the woman's mental and emotional state, cultural values, and coping ability.\n\n### Recognizing Labor\n\nSigns of impending labor include Braxton Hicks becoming more regular, bloody show, ruptured membranes, lightening/dropping, energy burst (nesting), and weight loss. True labor produces regular contractions that increase in frequency and intensity, cause progressive cervical change, and continue despite position changes. False labor contractions are irregular, do not cause cervical change, and often stop with rest.\n\n### The Cardinal Movements\n\nThe fetus navigates the birth canal through seven cardinal movements in sequence: Descent, Engagement, Flexion, Internal Rotation, Extension, External Rotation, and Expulsion. Understanding this sequence helps anticipate what is happening during each phase of labor.\n\n### Stages of Labor\n\n**First stage** (longest): cervical dilation from 0-10 cm and effacement to 100%, typically 4-6 hours. **Second stage**: expulsion of the fetus, 30 minutes to 2 hours. **Third stage**: delivery of the placenta, 5-30 minutes \u2014 either \"Shiny Schulze\" (fetal side first) or \"Dirty Duncan\" (maternal side first). **Fourth stage**: recovery, first 1-2 hours postpartum \u2014 critical monitoring period.\n\n### Fetal Heart Rate Monitoring\n\nNormal baseline FHR is 110-160 bpm. The **VEAL CHOP** mnemonic connects patterns to causes: Variable decelerations = Cord compression, Early decelerations = Head compression (benign), Accelerations = OK (reassuring), Late decelerations = Placental insufficiency (most concerning). Reassuring signs include moderate variability and accelerations. Non-reassuring signs include late decelerations, variable decelerations, and absent variability. FHR is monitored every 30 minutes in active first stage (every 15 minutes with risk factors) and every 15 minutes in second stage (every 5 minutes with risk factors).\n\nNormal amniotic fluid is clear with possible white vernix flecks. Green staining indicates meconium passage (possible fetal distress). Foul odor suggests infection.\n\n### Immediate Newborn Care\n\n**Apgar score** at 1 and 5 minutes assesses Heart rate, Respiratory effort, Muscle tone, Reflex response, and Color (0-2 each, 7-10 is normal). Phase 1 care (birth to 1 hour): thermoregulation, cardiorespiratory support, identification, anomaly assessment, and bonding/breastfeeding promotion. Two routine medications: erythromycin eye ointment (prevents ophthalmia neonatorum) and Vitamin K (AquaMEPHYTON, prevents hemorrhagic disease).\n\n---\n\n## Part 5: Pain Management During Labor (Ch. 7)\n\n### Understanding Childbirth Pain\n\nChildbirth pain is unique: it is part of a normal process, the woman has months to prepare, and it is self-limiting (rapidly resolves after birth). Factors influencing pain perception include pain threshold, CNS factors (gate control theory and endorphins), cervical readiness, pelvis shape, labor intensity, fatigue, and fetal position. The gate control theory explains why touch, massage, and counterpressure work \u2014 non-painful stimuli \"close the gate\" to pain signals.\n\n### Nonpharmacologic Approaches\n\nThree established methods are Dick-Read (education to break the fear-tension-pain cycle), Bradley (partner-coached natural birth), and Lamaze (patterned breathing, relaxation, focused concentration). Techniques include effleurage (light rhythmic abdominal stroking), breathing patterns, relaxation, and counterpressure. Key advantages: no harm to mother or fetus, no drug side effects, and will not slow labor.\n\nHyperventilation is a common complication of breathing techniques. Signs include dizziness, tingling in hands and feet, numbness around the nose and mouth, and hand cramps/spasms. Correction: slow breathing (especially on exhale), breathing into cupped hands, moist washcloth over mouth and nose, or briefly holding breath before exhaling.\n\n### Pharmacologic Approaches\n\nAn analgesic blocks pain while preserving motor function. An anesthetic blocks both pain and motor responses. The critical consideration: two patients are being medicated \u2014 the mother and the fetus. Opioid analgesics should be avoided if birth is anticipated within 1 hour due to risk of neonatal respiratory depression (reversible with naloxone). Medications can slow labor if given too early but can also reduce the maternal stress response that might otherwise cause fetal acidosis.\n\nFive types of anesthesia for childbirth: local infiltration (small area repair), pudendal block (perineal area), epidural (most common for labor), subarachnoid/spinal (for cesarean), and general anesthesia (emergencies only). The most serious maternal risk of general anesthesia is aspiration of gastric contents \u2014 heightened in pregnancy due to delayed gastric emptying.\n\n---\n\n## Part 6: Labor Complications (Ch. 8)\n\n### Obstetric Procedures\n\n**Bishop score** (assessing cervical readiness) of 6 or above predicts successful labor induction. Cervical ripening may be needed before oxytocin. **Amniotomy** (artificial ROM) stimulates contractions but commits the woman to delivery; watch for cord prolapse and infection. Perineal lacerations range from first degree (superficial) through fourth degree (extending through the rectal mucosa). Cesarean birth incisions: low transverse allows future VBAC with least rupture risk; classic vertical has the highest rupture risk.\n\n### Abnormal Labor (Dystocia)\n\nProblems can arise from any of the four Ps: inadequate powers (ineffective contractions or pushing), problems with the passage (small or abnormally shaped pelvis), problems with the passenger (malpresentation, macrosomia, multiples), or psychological factors (anxiety, lack of support, uncontrolled pain). Positions that help with malpresentation include sitting/kneeling while leaning forward, hands-and-knees rocking, side-lying, and squatting.\n\n### Preterm Labor\n\nRisk factors include previous preterm birth, infection, multiples, PROM, substance abuse, and inadequate prenatal care. The fetal fibronectin test (positive between 22-24 weeks) predicts preterm labor risk. A shortened cervix on ultrasound at 20 weeks is also predictive. Treatment: tocolytics to stop contractions (terbutaline, nifedipine, magnesium sulfate) plus betamethasone to accelerate fetal lung maturity \u2014 ideally given 48 hours before delivery. Tocolytics are contraindicated in preeclampsia, placenta previa, abruption, gestational age over 37 weeks, and fetal demise.\n\n### Obstetric Emergencies\n\n**Prolapsed umbilical cord**: the cord slips between the presenting part and the cervix after membrane rupture. Immediate actions: position the mother in knee-chest, insert a gloved hand to lift the presenting part off the cord, do NOT attempt to push the cord back in, and prepare for emergency C-section. **Amniotic fluid embolism**: amniotic fluid enters maternal circulation, causing respiratory failure and DIC. Treatment is supportive: respiratory support, treat shock, replace clotting factors, and transfer to ICU. **Uterine rupture**: can be complete, incomplete, or dehiscence \u2014 requires emergency surgery.\n\n---\n\n## Part 7: Postpartum Care (Ch. 9)\n\n### The BUBBLE Assessment\n\nThis systematic assessment guides postpartum nursing care: **B**reasts (soft versus engorged, nipple condition), **U**terus (firmness, fundal height, and position \u2014 should be firm, midline, descending 1-2 cm per day), **B**ladder (distention \u2014 a full bladder displaces the uterus and increases bleeding risk), **B**owels (return of bowel function, constipation management), **L**ochia (amount, color, odor, clots), and **E**pisiotomy/perineum (assessed using REEDA: Redness, Edema, Ecchymosis, Discharge, Approximation).\n\n### Lochia Progression\n\n**Lochia rubra** (days 1-3): red, mostly blood. **Lochia serosa** (days 4-10): pinkish, blood mixed with mucus. **Lochia alba** (days 10-21): white to clear, mostly mucus. A return to rubra after progressing to serosa or alba, or lochia with a foul odor, warrants immediate investigation.\n\n### Uterine Involution\n\nThe uterus should descend approximately 1-2 cm per day and be non-palpable by day 10, returning to pre-pregnant size by 5-6 weeks. A boggy (soft) fundus indicates uterine atony \u2014 the number one cause of postpartum hemorrhage. A fundus displaced to the right suggests a full bladder.\n\n### Perineum and Recovery\n\nIce packs for the first 12-24 hours reduce swelling. After 24 hours, sitz baths promote healing through increased circulation. Perineal pads should be applied front to back. Vaginal rugae reappear around 3 weeks postpartum. Sexual intercourse is generally safe when bleeding has stopped and the perineum has healed (usually 6 weeks).\n\n### Breastfeeding\n\n**Prolactin** (anterior pituitary) drives milk production. **Oxytocin** (posterior pituitary) triggers the let-down reflex. Milk progresses through three stages: **colostrum** (first few days \u2014 yellowish, rich in immunoglobulins, has a laxative effect to clear meconium), **transitional milk** (days 7-10), and **mature milk** (by day 14 \u2014 bluish color, 20 kcal/oz). **Foremilk** comes first at each feeding; **hindmilk** follows with higher fat content to satisfy hunger. Feeding every 2-3 hours should produce 8-10 wet diapers daily. Breast engorgement typically occurs around day 3 \u2014 frequent feeding is essential. The only absolute contraindications are HIV and HTLV 1 and 2.\n\nBreast milk storage: room temperature for up to 3 hours, refrigerator for up to 3 days, standard freezer for up to 3 months.\n\n### Psychosocial Adaptation\n\n**Rubin's phases**: Taking-in (first 1-2 days \u2014 dependent, focused on own needs), Taking-hold (days 2-7 \u2014 becoming independent, ready to learn), and Letting-go (adjusting to new role and responsibilities). Fathers and siblings also undergo role adjustments.\n\n### Discharge Teaching\n\nFollow-up appointments, hygiene, sexual intercourse timing, diet and exercise, danger signs to report, and newborn care. Car seat safety: rear-facing in the back seat until age 2, with the harness snugly fastened.\n\n---\n\n## Part 8: Postpartum Complications (Ch. 10)\n\n### Postpartum Hemorrhage\n\nEarly hemorrhage occurs within 24 hours; late hemorrhage occurs between 24 hours and 6 weeks. The **4 T's** identify causes: **T**one (uterine atony \u2014 the most common), **T**rauma (lacerations, hematomas), **T**issue (retained placental fragments), and **T**hrombin (clotting disorders). The earliest sign of hypovolemic shock is tachycardia, not hypotension. Treatment: fundal massage, bladder emptying, and medications (oxytocin, methylergonovine/Methergine, prostaglandins). A bright red bleed with a firm uterus suggests a laceration rather than atony.\n\n**Subinvolution** is a slower-than-expected return of the uterus to its non-pregnant state. Signs include fundal height greater than expected, persistent lochia rubra, and pelvic pain. Treatment may include Methergine, antibiotics, or D&C to remove retained placental fragments.\n\n### Thromboembolic Disorders\n\nPregnancy creates a hypercoagulable state (elevated fibrinogen, venous stasis, possible pressure from stirrups). **Superficial vein thrombosis** is treated with heat, elevation, and analgesics. **Deep vein thrombosis** requires anticoagulation (heparin or LMWH/Lovenox), and diagnosis is confirmed by ultrasound \u2014 look for leg circumference more than 2 cm greater than the other side with redness and tenderness. **Pulmonary embolism** presents with sudden chest pain, dyspnea, cough, and possibly hemoptysis \u2014 this requires ICU care. Prevention: early ambulation, SCDs, ROM exercises, and avoiding pressure behind the knees.\n\n### Postpartum Infections\n\n**Puerperal sepsis** is infection after childbirth with fever of 100.4 degrees F or higher within the first 10 days postpartum. **Endometritis** (inflammation of the uterine lining) is the most common cause of postpartum fever. Risk factors include surgical incisions, tissue trauma, retained placenta, and cracked nipples.\n\n**Mastitis** is a breast infection \u2014 typically unilateral with localized redness, warmth, and pain. Critical teaching point: continue breastfeeding (or pumping) because weaning during mastitis worsens symptoms by causing engorgement and milk stasis. Treatment includes antibiotics, warm compresses before feeding, ice after feeding, massage to improve milk flow, and adequate fluids.\n\n### Postpartum Mood Disorders\n\n**Postpartum blues** (days 1-10): tearfulness, mood swings, anxiety \u2014 common and self-resolving. **Postpartum depression** (onset 2-4 weeks): persistent sadness, inability to cope, guilt, sleep and appetite disturbance, lack of interest \u2014 requires treatment. Risk factors include inadequate social support, poor partner relationship, low self-esteem, and unplanned pregnancy. **Postpartum psychosis**: impaired reality perception, possible hallucinations \u2014 this is a psychiatric emergency.\n\nNursing tip: never assume a depressed postpartum patient simply has \"baby blues.\" Explore her feelings and assess for persistence and severity.\n\n---\n\n## Part 9: The Term Newborn (Ch. 12)\n\n### Neurological Assessment\n\nNormal head circumference is 32-36 cm and should not exceed the chest circumference by more than 2 cm. **Fontanelles** should be flat with the skull contour \u2014 bulging suggests increased intracranial pressure while depression suggests dehydration. Common birth-related head findings: **molding** (overlapping skull bones from birth canal pressure \u2014 normal, resolves), **caput succedaneum** (soft tissue swelling that crosses suture lines \u2014 resolves quickly), and **cephalohematoma** (bleeding under the periosteum that does NOT cross suture lines \u2014 resolves within weeks). Low-set ears may indicate congenital abnormalities.\n\n### Thermoregulation\n\nNewborns have an unstable heat-regulating system (normal temp 36.2-37.7 degrees C). They lose heat through four mechanisms: **evaporation** (wet skin \u2014 dry immediately after birth), **conduction** (contact with cold surfaces \u2014 use warm blankets, skin-to-skin), **convection** (air currents \u2014 avoid drafts), and **radiation** (proximity to cold objects \u2014 keep away from cold walls/windows). Sweat glands do not function in the neonatal period, so overheating from overdressing or overheated environments is also a risk. Acrocyanosis (bluish hands and feet) is normal due to sluggish peripheral circulation.\n\n### Key Reflexes\n\n**Rooting** \u2014 touch the cheek, baby turns toward the stimulus (essential for feeding). **Sucking** \u2014 place object in mouth, baby sucks. **Moro (startle)** \u2014 sudden noise or movement causes arms to extend outward then flex inward. **Palmar grasp** \u2014 object placed in palm is gripped tightly. These reflexes disappear at predictable ages as the nervous system matures.\n\n### Gastrointestinal Function\n\nStool progression: **meconium** (dark greenish-black, sterile \u2014 passed in first 24-48 hours) transitions to **transitional stool**, then to **breast-fed stool** (yellow, seedy, mild odor) or **formula-fed stool** (pale yellow, firmer). Breast-fed infants may need supplemental Vitamins C and D. Bottle propping is unsafe due to choking, ear infection, and tooth decay risk.\n\n### Neonatal Hypoglycemia\n\nBlood glucose below 45 mg/dL in a term infant indicates hypoglycemia. High-risk groups: preterm or postterm infants, infants of diabetic mothers, LGA or SGA infants, those with IUGR, asphyxia, cold stress, or whose mothers received tocolytics. Signs include jitteriness, poor muscle tone, sweating, respiratory difficulty, low temperature, poor suck, high-pitched cry, lethargy, and seizures.\n\n### Infection Prevention and Cord Care\n\nThe newborn immune system is immature, making infection response slow. **Hand hygiene** is the primary prevention measure. The umbilical cord stump should be kept clean and dry, with the diaper fastened below it to allow air circulation. Parents should report redness, moisture, or foul smell. Sponge baths are preferred until the cord stump falls off.\n\n### Discharge Readiness\n\nBefore discharge: hearing screening, metabolic screening, car seat check (rear-facing in back seat until age 2), feeding established, vital signs stable, and parents educated on danger signs, feeding, cord care, and follow-up appointments.\n\n---\n\n*This guide covers all testable content areas for the ATI CMS Maternal Newborn assessment. For highest yield, focus on fetal circulation shunts and their closure times, Nagele's rule calculations, the BUBBLE postpartum assessment, lochia progression, FHR pattern interpretation (VEAL CHOP), preeclampsia management and the role of magnesium sulfate, the 4 T's of postpartum hemorrhage, breastfeeding physiology, and newborn thermoregulation mechanisms.*\n";

window.studyGuideContent["ob_ch678_cheatsheet"] = "# OB Cheat Sheet: Labor & Birth, Pain Management & Complications\n### Chapters 6, 7 & 8 \u2014 Quick Review\n\n---\n\n## \ud83e\udd31 CHAPTER 6: LABOR & BIRTH\n\n### The Four \"P's\" of Labor\n| P | Meaning |\n|---|---------|\n| **Powers** | Uterine contractions + maternal pushing |\n| **Passage** | Bony pelvis + soft tissues |\n| **Passenger** | Fetus (size, presentation, position) |\n| **Psyche** | Mental/emotional state of mother |\n\n### Additional Factors (6 P's)\nPreparation \u2022 Position \u2022 Professional \u2022 Place \u2022 Procedures \u2022 People\n\n### Uterine Contractions\n| Term | Meaning |\n|------|---------|\n| **Effacement** | Thinning/shortening of the cervical canal (0-100%) |\n| **Dilation** | Opening of the cervical os (0-10 cm) |\n| **Frequency** | Time from start of one contraction to start of next |\n| **Duration** | Length of contraction (start \u2192 end) |\n| **Intensity** | Strength: mild / moderate / firm |\n\n### Three Phases of a Contraction\n1. **Increment** (building)\n2. **Peak/Acme** (strongest)\n3. **Decrement** (letting up)\n\n### Signs of Impending Labor\n- Braxton Hicks \u2192 more regular\n- **Bloody show** (mucus plug + blood)\n- Rupture of membranes\n- **Lightening/dropping** (baby descends)\n- Energy spurt (\"nesting\")\n- Weight loss, loose stools\n\n### True vs. False Labor\n| True Labor | False Labor |\n|------------|-------------|\n| Contractions **regular**, \u2191 frequency/intensity | Irregular, no pattern |\n| Continue despite position change | May stop with rest/position change |\n| **Cervical change** (effacement/dilation) | No cervical change |\n| Progressive | Non-progressive |\n\n### When to Go to Hospital \u2b50\n**3-2-1 Rule** (primipara): Contractions **3 min apart, lasting 1 min, for 1 hour**\n- Ruptured membranes\n- Bleeding (other than bloody show)\n- Decreased fetal movement\n- Any concern\n\n### Mechanisms (Cardinal Movements) of Labor\n> **D \u2192 E \u2192 F \u2192 I \u2192 E \u2192 E \u2192 Ex**\n> **Descent \u2192 Engagement \u2192 Flexion \u2192 Internal rotation \u2192 Extension \u2192 External rotation \u2192 Expulsion**\n\n### Stages of Labor\n| Stage | Name | Duration | What Happens |\n|-------|------|----------|--------------|\n| **First** | Dilation & Effacement | 4-6 hrs | Longest stage; 0-10 cm dilation |\n| **Second** | Expulsion | 30 min - 2 hrs | Baby born |\n| **Third** | Placenta | 5-30 min | Placenta delivered (Schultze/Duncan) |\n| **Fourth** | Recovery | 1-2 hrs | Hemorrhage prevention, bonding |\n\n### Fetal Heart Rate (FHR)\n| Finding | Normal/Abnormal |\n|---------|-----------------|\n| **Baseline** | **110-160 bpm** |\n| **Bradycardia** | <110 bpm |\n| **Tachycardia** | >160 bpm |\n| **Moderate variability** | \u2705 Reassuring |\n| **Absent/Minimal variability** | \u26a0\ufe0f Concerning |\n| **Accelerations** | \u2705 Reassuring |\n\n### FHR Decelerations \u2014 VEAL CHOP \u2b50\n| Deceleration | Cause | Intervention |\n|--------------|-------|--------------|\n| **V**ariable | **C**ord compression | Reposition, O2, amnioinfusion |\n| **E**arly | **H**ead compression | None (normal) |\n| **A**cceleration | **O**K (good!) | None |\n| **L**ate | **P**lacental insufficiency | O2, reposition, stop Pitocin, notify MD |\n\n### Amniotic Fluid Assessment\n| Finding | Meaning |\n|---------|---------|\n| Clear + white flecks (vernix) | \u2705 Normal |\n| **Green/meconium** | \u26a0\ufe0f Fetal distress, MAS risk |\n| Foul odor | \u26a0\ufe0f Infection |\n| Scant vs. large | Assess amount |\n\n### Apgar Score (at 1 and 5 min)\n| Component | 0 | 1 | 2 |\n|-----------|---|---|---|\n| Heart rate | Absent | <100 | \u2265100 |\n| Respirations | Absent | Slow/irregular | Good cry |\n| Muscle tone | Flaccid | Some flexion | Active motion |\n| Reflex irritability | None | Grimace | Cry/cough |\n| Color | Blue/pale | Body pink, extremities blue | All pink |\n\n> **7-10** = Normal | **4-6** = Moderate distress | **0-3** = Severe distress\n\n### Newborn Medications Immediately After Birth\n| Medication | Purpose |\n|------------|---------|\n| **Vitamin K (AquaMEPHYTON)** | Prevents hemorrhagic disease (vit K deficiency) |\n| **Erythromycin eye ointment** | Prevents gonococcal/chlamydial ophthalmia neonatorum |\n\n### Immediate Newborn Care (Phase 1: Birth \u2192 1 hr)\n- Maintain **thermoregulation** (warm, dry, skin-to-skin)\n- Maintain **cardiorespiratory function**\n- Observe for urination/meconium\n- Identify mother/father/infant\n- Brief anomaly assessment\n- Encourage bonding/breastfeeding\n\n### VBAC (Vaginal Birth After Cesarean)\n- Main concern: **uterine scar rupture**\n- Low transverse incision = best candidate\n- Provide **extra emotional support**\n\n### Immediate Postpartum (4th Stage)\n- **Prevent hemorrhage**: fundal massage, assess lochia\n- Monitor VS, bladder output\n- Ice to perineum\n- Keep warm and dry\n- Promote bonding\n\n---\n\n## \ud83d\udc8a CHAPTER 7: PAIN MANAGEMENT IN LABOR\n\n### Childbirth Preparation Methods\n| Method | Focus |\n|--------|-------|\n| **Dick-Read** | Education reduces fear \u2192 reduces pain |\n| **Bradley** | Husband-coached, natural childbirth |\n| **Lamaze** | Breathing, relaxation, focal points |\n\n### Nonpharmacologic Pain Relief\n- **Effleurage** (light abdominal stroking)\n- Breathing techniques (patterned, slow)\n- Position changes, hydrotherapy, massage\n- Visualization, music, aromatherapy\n- **Doula/birth support**\n\n\u26a0\ufe0f **Hyperventilation signs**: Dizziness, tingling hands/feet, muscle cramps, blurred vision\n\u2192 **Fix**: Breathe into cupped hands, slow exhalation\n\n### Pharmacologic Pain Management\n\n**Systemic Analgesics** (opioids)\n- Given early in labor (not within 1 hr of birth)\n- Can cause **neonatal respiratory depression**\n- **Naloxone (Narcan)** = antidote\n\n**Regional Anesthesia**\n| Type | Block Area | Notes |\n|------|------------|-------|\n| **Epidural** | T10-S5 | Most common; continuous infusion |\n| **Spinal (subarachnoid)** | Lower body | Single dose; rapid onset |\n| **Pudendal** | Perineum | Vaginal birth, episiotomy |\n| **Local infiltration** | Perineum | For episiotomy repair |\n\n**General Anesthesia**\n- Emergency C-section only\n- Risk: **aspiration** \u2192 chemical lung injury\n- Neonatal respiratory depression\n\n### Pregnancy Physiology & Anesthesia\n- \u2191 Aspiration risk (sluggish GI)\n- **Aortocaval compression** \u2192 hypotension (left lateral tilt)\n- \u2191 Hypoxia risk\n- All medications affect **both mother and fetus**\n\n---\n\n## \u26a0\ufe0f CHAPTER 8: LABOR & BIRTH COMPLICATIONS\n\n### Induction vs. Augmentation\n| Term | Meaning |\n|------|---------|\n| **Induction** | Starting labor artificially (before it begins) |\n| **Augmentation** | Stimulating contractions that have already started |\n\n### Bishop Score \u2b50\n> Assesses cervical readiness for induction\n> **Score >6** = favorable for induction\n\nComponents: dilation, effacement, station, consistency, position\n\n### Contraindications to Induction\n- **Cephalopelvic disproportion (CPD)**\n- **Placenta previa**\n- **Active herpes infection**\n- Fetal malpresentation, umbilical cord prolapsed, previous classical C-section\n\n### Amniotomy (AROM)\n> Artificial rupture of membranes\n> Commits woman to delivery\n\n**Complications**: Cord prolapse, infection, abruption\n\n### Amnioinfusion\nWarmed saline infused into uterus via IUPC\n- **Indications**: Oligohydramnios, cord compression (variable decels), dilute meconium\n\n### Perineal Lacerations\n| Degree | Structures Involved |\n|--------|---------------------|\n| **1st** | Vaginal mucosa, perineal skin |\n| **2nd** | + Deeper perineal tissues |\n| **3rd** | + Anal sphincter |\n| **4th** | + Rectal mucosa |\n\n### Cesarean Birth\n**Indications**: CPD, breech, placenta previa, fetal distress, failed induction, maternal disease, previous C-section\n\n**Incision Types**:\n| Incision | Location | VBAC? |\n|----------|----------|-------|\n| **Low transverse** (Pfannenstiel) | Skin + uterine | \u2705 Yes |\n| Low vertical | Less common | \u26a0\ufe0f Riskier |\n| **Classic** | Upper uterine segment | \u274c No |\n\n**Risks to mother**: Anesthesia, hemorrhage, blood clots, UTI, paralytic ileus, infection\n\n### Dystocia (Difficult Labor)\nCaused by abnormality of:\n- **Power** (contractions)\n- **Passenger** (fetus size, presentation, position)\n- **Passage** (pelvis)\n- **Psyche** (anxiety, lack of support)\n\n### Abnormal Fetal Positions\n- **Occiput posterior (OP)**: \"Back labor\" \u2192 **hands/knees, pelvic rocking**\n- **Breech**: Buttocks or feet first\n- Nursing: Encourage positions favoring rotation\n\n### Preterm Labor \u2b50\n**Risk Factors**: Previous PTL, infection, substance abuse, multifetal, inadequate prenatal care, dehydration, smoking, DES exposure, chronic stress\n\n**Symptoms**: Menstrual-like cramps, low backache, pelvic pressure, change in discharge, \"feeling bad\"\n\n**Fetal Fibronectin (fFN) Test**: Detects protein in vaginal fluid \u2192 predicts PTL risk (22-24 weeks)\n\n**Tocolytics** (stop contractions):\n| Drug | Notes |\n|------|-------|\n| **Magnesium sulfate** | Also neuroprotection; monitor RR (>12), DTRs; antidote = **calcium gluconate** |\n| **Terbutaline** | Tachycardia, tremors, hyperglycemia |\n| **Nifedipine** | Calcium channel blocker |\n\n**Betamethasone**: Given **48 hrs before** delivery (2 doses, 24 hrs apart) \u2192 accelerates fetal lung maturity\n\n### Obstetric Emergencies\n\n**Prolapsed Umbilical Cord**\n- Cord slips below presenting part \u2192 compresses \u2192 fetal hypoxia\n- **Immediate action**: **Knee-chest position**, push presenting part OFF cord, call for help, prepare for C-section\n- May ride on stretcher to OR with hand in place\n\n**Uterine Rupture**\n- Complete (through all layers), incomplete, dehiscence\n- Risk: prior C-section, trauma, hyperstimulation\n- Signs: sudden pain, hemorrhage, loss of contractions, fetal distress\n\n**Amniotic Fluid Embolism (Anaphylactoid Syndrome)**\n- Amniotic fluid enters maternal circulation\n- **Life-threatening**: respiratory arrest, shock, DIC\n- Tx: respiratory support, fluids, coagulation factors\n\n---\n\n*\ud83d\udcdd Focus on \u2b50 starred topics: VEAL CHOP, Bishop Score, Apgar, stages of labor, induction contraindications, and emergency interventions.*\n\n*Good luck on your exam!*\n";

window.studyGuideContent["ob_ch678_comprehensive"] = "# Comprehensive Study Guide: Labor & Birth, Pain Management & Complications\n### OB/Maternity Chapters 6, 7 & 8\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 6: Nursing Care of Mother and Infant During Labor and Birth\n\n### 1. Settings for Childbirth\n\n**Hospital Birth**\n- Advantages: Immediate access to emergency care, pain relief options, NICU available\n- Disadvantages: May feel less personal, higher intervention rates, less control over environment\n\n**Freestanding Birth Centers**\n- Advantages: Home-like setting, lower intervention rates, certified nurse-midwives\n- Disadvantages: Must transfer to hospital for complications, limited pain relief options\n\n**Home Birth**\n- Advantages: Familiar environment, family-centered, lower costs\n- Disadvantages: No immediate access to surgical/emergency care, limited pain relief\n\n### 2. The Four \"P's\" of the Birth Process\n\n**Powers** \u2014 Uterine contractions and maternal pushing effort\n- Primary power: involuntary uterine contractions that cause cervical effacement and dilation\n- Secondary power: voluntary bearing-down effort by the mother\n\n**Passage** \u2014 The birth canal\n- Bony pelvis (true pelvis with inlet, midpelvis, outlet)\n- Soft tissues (cervix, vagina, pelvic floor)\n\n**Passenger** \u2014 The fetus\n- Size, presentation (part entering pelvis first), position (relationship to maternal pelvis), lie (longitudinal vs. transverse)\n\n**Psyche** \u2014 Mental and emotional state\n- Anxiety, fear, cultural beliefs, support system all influence labor progress\n\n### 3. Additional Factors Affecting Labor (6 P's)\n\nBeyond the four P's, labor is influenced by:\n1. **Preparation** \u2014 Prenatal education and birth planning\n2. **Position** \u2014 Maternal positioning during labor\n3. **Professional** \u2014 Skills and approach of the birth attendant\n4. **Place** \u2014 Physical environment of birth\n5. **Procedures** \u2014 Interventions performed\n6. **People** \u2014 Support persons present\n\n### 4. Uterine Contractions\n\n**Effect on the Cervix**:\n- **Effacement**: Thinning and shortening of the cervical canal from 0% (thick) to 100% (paper-thin)\n- **Dilation**: Opening of the cervical os from 0 cm to 10 cm (complete)\n\n**Phases of a Contraction**:\n1. **Increment** \u2014 Contraction builds in intensity\n2. **Peak (Acme)** \u2014 Strongest point of contraction\n3. **Decrement** \u2014 Contraction subsides\n\n**Assessment Terms**:\n- **Frequency**: Time from start of one contraction to start of the next (e.g., every 3 minutes)\n- **Duration**: Length of one contraction (e.g., 60 seconds)\n- **Intensity**: Strength \u2014 mild, moderate, or firm (assessed by palpation or IUPC)\n\n### 5. Signs of Impending Labor\n\n- **Braxton Hicks contractions**: Irregular, painless \"practice\" contractions that become more regular near term\n- **Increased vaginal discharge**: Clear or slightly bloody\n- **Bloody show**: Mucus plug expelled with small amount of blood \u2014 reliable sign\n- **Rupture of membranes**: May be a gush or trickle of amniotic fluid\n- **Energy spurt (\"nesting\")**: Sudden burst of energy to prepare home/baby area\n- **Weight loss**: 1-3 lbs from fluid shifts\n- **Lightening/dropping**: Baby descends into pelvis; mother may breathe easier but have more bladder pressure\n- **Loose bowel movements**: Muscles relax in preparation\n\n### 6. True vs. False Labor\n\n| Feature | True Labor | False Labor |\n|---------|------------|-------------|\n| **Contractions** | Regular pattern, \u2191 frequency and intensity | Irregular, no progressive pattern |\n| **Cervical change** | Progressive effacement and dilation | No change |\n| **Effect of position change** | Contractions continue | May stop or decrease |\n| **Pain location** | Starts in back, radiates to abdomen | May be felt in abdomen only |\n| **Walking** | Intensifies contractions | May relieve discomfort |\n\n### 7. When to Go to the Hospital\n\n**3-2-1 Rule** (especially for first-time mothers):\n- Contractions are **3 minutes apart**\n- Lasting **1 minute (60 seconds)** each\n- Continuing for at least **1 hour**\n\nOther indications:\n- Ruptured membranes\n- Vaginal bleeding (other than bloody show)\n- Decreased or absent fetal movement\n- Any other concern\n\n### 8. Mechanisms (Cardinal Movements) of Labor\n\nThese are the positional changes the fetal head makes as it navigates the birth canal:\n\n1. **Descent** \u2014 Baby moves down through the pelvis\n2. **Engagement** \u2014 Widest diameter of fetal head enters pelvic inlet\n3. **Flexion** \u2014 Chin tucks to chest (smallest diameter presents)\n4. **Internal Rotation** \u2014 Head rotates to align with pelvic outlet\n5. **Extension** \u2014 Head extends as it passes under pubis\n6. **External Rotation (Restitution)** \u2014 Head rotates back to align with shoulders\n7. **Expulsion** \u2014 Shoulders and body deliver\n\n### 9. Stages and Phases of Labor\n\n**First Stage: Dilation and Effacement** (longest stage \u2014 4-6 hours average)\n- **Latent phase**: 0-3 cm dilation; contractions mild, irregular\n- **Active phase**: 4-7 cm dilation; contractions stronger, more frequent\n- **Transition phase**: 8-10 cm dilation; most intense, shortest\n\n**Second Stage: Expulsion** (30 minutes to 2 hours)\n- Full dilation to birth of baby\n- Mother actively pushes with contractions\n\n**Third Stage: Placental Expulsion** (5-30 minutes)\n- Placenta separates from uterine wall and delivers\n- **Schultze mechanism**: Placenta delivers \"shiny side\" (fetal surface) first\n- **Duncan mechanism**: Placenta delivers \"dirty side\" (maternal surface) first\n\n**Fourth Stage: Recovery** (1-2 hours postpartum)\n- Critical period for hemorrhage prevention\n- Uterus must contract firmly to clamp blood vessels\n- Bonding and initial newborn care occur\n\n### 10. Admission to the Labor Unit\n\n**Three Major Assessments Performed Promptly**:\n1. **Fetal condition** \u2014 FHR, amniotic fluid status\n2. **Maternal condition** \u2014 VS, contractions, progress of labor\n3. **Impending birth** \u2014 Is delivery imminent?\n\n**Admission Procedures**:\n- Permits and consents\n- Laboratory tests (CBC, type/Rh, urinalysis)\n- IV placement\n- Perineal prep (if needed)\n- Determining fetal position and presentation (Leopold maneuvers, vaginal exam)\n\n### 11. Fetal Heart Rate Monitoring\n\n**Baseline FHR**: 110-160 beats/min\n\n**Monitoring Frequency**:\n- **Low-risk, active first stage**: Every 30 minutes\n- **Second stage**: Every 15 minutes, preferably before each contraction\n- **With risk factors**: Every 15 minutes (first stage), every 5 minutes (second stage)\n\n**Methods**:\n- **Intermittent auscultation**: Listening with Doppler or fetoscope\n- **Continuous electronic fetal monitoring (EFM)**: External (ultrasound transducer + toco) or internal (fetal scalp electrode + IUPC)\n\n### 12. FHR Patterns \u2014 Reassuring vs. Nonreassuring\n\n**Reassuring Patterns**:\n- Stable baseline FHR within normal range\n- **Moderate variability** (fluctuations of 6-25 bpm)\n- **Accelerations** (\u2191 15 bpm \u00d7 15 sec \u2014 \"reassuring\")\n- Contractions >2 min apart with \u226560 sec relaxation between\n\n**Nonreassuring Patterns**:\n- Tachycardia or bradycardia\n- Decreased or absent variability\n- **Late decelerations** (begin after contraction peak \u2014 placental insufficiency)\n- **Variable decelerations** (abrupt drops \u2014 cord compression)\n\n### 13. VEAL CHOP \u2014 Deceleration Mnemonic \u2b50\n\n| Letter | Deceleration | Cause | Intervention |\n|--------|--------------|-------|--------------|\n| **V** | Variable | **C**ord compression | Reposition mother, O2, amnioinfusion |\n| **E** | Early | **H**ead compression | None (normal finding) |\n| **A** | Acceleration | **O**K! | None (reassuring) |\n| **L** | Late | **P**lacental insufficiency | O2, left lateral position, stop Pitocin, notify provider |\n\n### 14. Amniotic Fluid Assessment\n\n**Color**:\n- Clear with white flecks of vernix = normal\n- **Green or meconium-stained** = fetus passed stool; possible fetal compromise, risk of meconium aspiration syndrome (MAS)\n\n**Odor**:\n- Should be odorless\n- Foul odor suggests infection\n\n**Amount**:\n- Scant: trickle\n- Moderate: ~500 mL\n- Large: \u22651000 mL\n\n### 15. Apgar Scoring\n\nPerformed at **1 minute** and **5 minutes** after birth:\n\n| Component | 0 | 1 | 2 |\n|-----------|---|---|---|\n| **Heart rate** | Absent | <100 bpm | \u2265100 bpm |\n| **Respiratory effort** | Absent | Slow, irregular | Good cry |\n| **Muscle tone** | Flaccid | Some flexion | Active motion |\n| **Reflex irritability** | None | Grimace | Cry or cough |\n| **Color** | Blue/pale all over | Body pink, extremities blue | Completely pink |\n\n**Interpretation**:\n- 7-10: Normal\n- 4-6: Moderate depression; may need stimulation and oxygen\n- 0-3: Severe depression; needs aggressive resuscitation\n\n### 16. Immediate Newborn Care (Phase 1: Birth to 1 Hour)\n\n- **Maintain thermoregulation**: Dry baby, place skin-to-skin, warm blankets, radiant warmer\n- **Maintain cardiorespiratory function**: Suction airway if needed, assess respirations\n- **Observe for urination and passage of meconium**\n- **Identify mother, father, and newborn** (bracelets)\n- **Brief assessment for major anomalies**\n- **Encourage bonding and breastfeeding** (golden hour)\n\n### 17. Newborn Medications\n\n**Vitamin K (AquaMEPHYTON)**:\n- Given IM in vastus lateralis\n- Prevents hemorrhagic disease of the newborn (vitamin K deficiency bleeding)\n\n**Erythromycin Eye Ointment**:\n- Applied to both eyes\n- Prevents ophthalmia neonatorum (gonococcal/chlamydial conjunctivitis)\n\n### 18. VBAC (Vaginal Birth After Cesarean)\n\n**Main concern**: Uterine scar rupture\n- Can disrupt placental blood flow\n- Lead to hemorrhage\n\n**Nursing care**:\n- Woman may need more support than other laboring women\n- Provide empathy and encouragement\n- Monitor for signs of rupture (sudden pain, FHR changes, hemorrhage)\n\n### 19. Immediate Postpartum Period (Third and Fourth Stages)\n\n**Third Stage (placental delivery)**:\n- Observe for signs of placental separation (gush of blood, lengthening cord, fundus rises)\n- Schultze or Duncan presentation\n\n**Fourth Stage Nursing Care**:\n- Identify and prevent hemorrhage (fundal massage, assess lochia)\n- Evaluate and intervene for pain\n- Observe bladder function and urine output\n- Evaluate recovery from anesthesia\n- Provide initial care to newborn\n- Promote bonding and attachment\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 7: Nursing Management of Pain During Labor and Birth\n\n### 1. Childbirth and Pain \u2014 How It Differs\n\nUnlike other types of pain:\n- Part of a **normal birth process**\n- Woman has **months to prepare** for pain management\n- **Self-limiting** \u2014 rapidly declines after birth\n- Associated with a **positive outcome** (baby!)\n\n### 2. Factors That Influence Labor Pain\n\n**Pain Threshold**: Individual variation in how pain is perceived\n\n**Sources of Pain**:\n- Cervical dilation and effacement\n- Uterine muscle ischemia (reduced blood flow during contractions)\n- Pressure on bladder, urethra, bowel\n- Stretching of birth canal\n\n**CNS Factors**:\n- **Gate control theory**: Non-painful stimuli (massage, pressure) can \"close the gate\" to pain signals\n- **Endorphins**: Natural pain-relieving hormones released during labor\n\n**Maternal Conditions**:\n- Cervical readiness (effaced, anterior = less painful)\n- Pelvis shape and size\n- Labor intensity and rapidity\n- Fatigue level\n- Fetal presentation and position (OP = more back pain)\n\n### 3. Childbirth Preparation Methods\n\n**Dick-Read Method**:\n- Fear \u2192 Tension \u2192 Pain cycle\n- Education and relaxation break this cycle\n- \"Childbirth Without Fear\"\n\n**Bradley Method**:\n- Husband-coached natural childbirth\n- Focus on nutrition, exercise, relaxation\n- Minimal intervention philosophy\n\n**Lamaze Method**:\n- Breathing techniques, focal points, relaxation\n- Partner support\n- Knowledge reduces fear\n\n### 4. Nonpharmacologic Pain Relief Measures\n\n**Advantages**:\n- No harm to mother or fetus\n- Do not slow labor if providing adequate pain control\n- No allergy or adverse drug effects\n\n**Techniques**:\n- **Effleurage**: Light, rhythmic stroking of the abdomen\n- **Breathing**: Slow, patterned, or accelerated-paced\n- Position changes\n- Hydrotherapy (shower, tub)\n- Massage and counterpressure\n- Heat/cold application\n- Visualization and imagery\n- Music and aromatherapy\n- **Doula**: Continuous labor support\n\n**Hyperventilation Recognition and Correction**:\n- Signs: Dizziness, tingling hands/feet, muscle cramps, numbness around nose/mouth, blurred vision\n- Correction: Breathe slowly, especially exhaling; breathe into cupped hands; place moist washcloth over nose/mouth; hold breath briefly before exhaling\n\n### 5. Pharmacologic Pain Management\n\n**Categories**:\n- **Analgesics**: Relieve pain (systemic or regional)\n- **Anesthetics**: Block sensation (regional or general)\n\n### 6. Systemic Analgesics\n\n**Narcotic (Opioid) Analgesics**:\n- Provide pain relief without loss of consciousness\n- Examples: fentanyl, morphine, nalbuphine\n- **Avoid if birth anticipated within 1 hour** (neonatal respiratory depression)\n\n**Narcotic Antagonist**:\n- **Naloxone (Narcan)**: Reverses respiratory depression in mother and newborn\n\n**Adjunctive Drugs**:\n- Relieve nausea and vomiting associated with opioids\n- Examples: promethazine, hydroxyzine\n\n### 7. Regional Anesthesia\n\nInvolves placing anesthetic in epidural or subarachnoid space around spinal cord.\n\n**Meninges (from outer to inner)**:\n1. Dura mater\n2. Arachnoid mater\n3. Pia mater\n\n**Difference Between Analgesic and Anesthetic**:\n- **Analgesic**: Blocks pain sensation\n- **Anesthetic**: Blocks both pain and motor responses\n\n### 8. Types of Regional Anesthesia for Childbirth\n\n| Type | Where Given | Effect | Notes |\n|------|-------------|--------|-------|\n| **Local infiltration** | Perineum | Numbs small area | For episiotomy/repair |\n| **Pudendal block** | Pudendal nerve (ischial spine) | Perineum numbed | Vaginal birth, forceps, vacuum |\n| **Epidural block** | Epidural space (T10-S5) | Pain relief; may retain motor | Continuous infusion; most common |\n| **Spinal (subarachnoid) block** | Subarachnoid space | Complete pain/motor block below level | Single dose; rapid onset; common for C-section |\n\n### 9. General Anesthesia\n\n**When Used**:\n- Emergency cesarean when not enough time for block\n- Cesarean in woman who refuses or has contraindication to regional\n\n**Adverse Effects \u2014 Mother**:\n- **Regurgitation with aspiration** of gastric contents \u2192 chemical lung injury\n- Respiratory depression\n\n**Adverse Effects \u2014 Newborn**:\n- **Respiratory depression**\n- Aggressive resuscitation may be necessary\n\n### 10. Pregnancy Physiology and Anesthesia\n\n- **\u2191 Hypoxia risk**: Reduced FRC, \u2191 O2 consumption\n- **Sluggish GI tract**: \u2191 Risk of vomiting and aspiration\n- **Aortocaval compression**: Uterus compresses IVC when supine \u2192 hypotension; **use left lateral tilt**\n- **Effect on fetus**: All medications cross placenta to some degree\n\n### 11. Nurse's Role in Pharmacologic Pain Management\n\n- Begins at admission: assess woman's preference for pain relief\n- Keep side rails up (sedation risk)\n- Provide education regarding procedures and expected effects\n- **Observe for hypotension** (especially after epidural/spinal)\n- **Observe for respiratory depression**\n- Document interventions and assessments\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 8: Nursing Care of Women with Complications During Labor and Birth\n\n### 1. Induction vs. Augmentation of Labor\n\n| Term | Definition |\n|------|------------|\n| **Induction** | Intentional initiation of labor before it occurs naturally |\n| **Augmentation** | Stimulation of contractions after they have started naturally |\n\n### 2. Bishop Score \u2b50\n\nA tool to assess cervical readiness for induction. A score **above 6** indicates the cervix is favorable for induction.\n\n**Components scored**:\n- Dilation (0-3 cm)\n- Effacement (0-80%)\n- Station (-3 to +3)\n- Cervical consistency (firm, medium, soft)\n- Cervical position (posterior, mid, anterior)\n\n### 3. Indications for Labor Induction\n\n- Post-term pregnancy\n- PROM (premature rupture of membranes)\n- Maternal medical conditions (preeclampsia, diabetes, cardiac disease)\n- Fetal compromise\n- Fetal demise\n- Chorioamnionitis\n\n### 4. Contraindications to Labor Induction\n\n- **Cephalopelvic disproportion (CPD)**\n- **Placenta previa**\n- **Active herpes infection**\n- Fetal malpresentation (breech, transverse)\n- Umbilical cord prolapsed\n- Previous classical cesarean incision\n- Active genital herpes\n\n### 5. Pharmacologic Methods to Stimulate Contractions\n\n**Oxytocin (Pitocin)**:\n- Most common agent for induction/augmentation\n- Must be titrated carefully\n- Nurse monitors contractions and FHR closely\n\n**Prostaglandins**:\n- **Cervidil (dinoprostone/PGE2)**: Vaginal insert for cervical ripening\n- **Cytotec (misoprostol/PGE1)**: Off-label use for cervical ripening\n\n### 6. Cervical Dilation Methods\n\n**Mechanical**:\n- **Laminaria**: Seaweed sticks that absorb moisture and expand\n- **Transcervical balloon dilators**: Balloon catheter inserted through cervical os and inflated\n\n**Pharmacologic**:\n- Prostaglandin preparations\n\n### 7. Amniotomy (AROM)\n\n**Artificial Rupture of Membranes**\n- Performed to stimulate or enhance contractions\n- **Commits the woman to delivery** (cannot delay birth)\n\n**Complications**:\n- **Prolapse of the umbilical cord**\n- **Infection**\n- **Abruptio placentae**\n\n**Nursing care**: Monitor FHR immediately after; observe fluid characteristics\n\n### 8. Amnioinfusion\n\n**Definition**: Infusion of warmed sterile saline or LR into the uterus via IUPC after membranes have ruptured\n\n**Indications**:\n- **Oligohydramnios** (too little fluid)\n- **Umbilical cord compression** causing variable decelerations\n- **Diluting meconium-stained amniotic fluid** to prevent MAS\n\n### 9. Version (External Cephalic Version)\n\n**Definition**: Manually turning a breech or transverse fetus to cephalic presentation\n\n**Performed**: Usually 37+ weeks if vaginal delivery desired\n\n**Contraindications**: Placenta previa, nonreassuring FHR, uterine anomalies, oligohydramnios\n\n### 10. Perineal Lacerations\n\n**Uncontrolled tearing of perineal tissue**:\n\n| Degree | Structures Involved |\n|--------|---------------------|\n| **First** | Superficial vaginal mucosa or perineal skin |\n| **Second** | Vaginal mucosa, perineal skin, and deeper tissues |\n| **Third** | Same as second + anal sphincter |\n| **Fourth** | Extends through anal sphincter into rectal mucosa |\n\n**Nursing care**: Comfort measures (ice, analgesics), wound assessment, sitz baths, stool softeners\n\n### 11. Episiotomy\n\n**Definition**: Surgical incision of the perineum to enlarge the vaginal opening\n\n**Types**: Midline (vertical) or mediolateral\n\n**Current practice**: Generally avoided unless medically necessary; spontaneous tears heal better\n\n### 12. Forceps and Vacuum Extraction\n\n**Indications**: Prolonged second stage, maternal exhaustion, fetal distress, maternal conditions that prohibit pushing\n\n**Risks**:\n- **Maternal**: Lacerations, hematomas, hemorrhage\n- **Fetal**: Bruising, facial/scalp lacerations, cephalohematoma, chignon (vacuum), retinal hemorrhage\n\n### 13. Cesarean Birth\n\n**Indications**:\n- CPD\n- Breech or other malpresentation\n- Placenta previa or abruption\n- Fetal distress\n- Failed induction or labor progress\n- Previous C-section (depending on type)\n- Maternal conditions (herpes, HIV, cardiac disease)\n\n**Incision Types**:\n\n| Skin Incision | Uterine Incision | VBAC Possible? |\n|---------------|------------------|----------------|\n| Transverse (Pfannenstiel) | Low transverse | \u2705 Yes |\n| Vertical | Low vertical | \u26a0\ufe0f Riskier |\n| \u2014 | **Classic** | \u274c No (highest rupture risk) |\n\n**Risks to Mother**:\n- Anesthesia complications\n- Hemorrhage\n- Blood clots (DVT/PE)\n- Injury to urinary tract\n- Delayed peristalsis (paralytic ileus)\n- Infection\n\n**Risks to Newborn**:\n- Inadvertent preterm birth\n- Respiratory problems (TTN, RDS)\n- Injury (bruising, laceration)\n\n### 14. Dystocia (Difficult Labor)\n\n**Definition**: Abnormal labor caused by abnormality of the \"four P's\"\n\n**Power (Contractions)**:\n- Hypotonic: Weak, ineffective contractions\n- Hypertonic: Excessive, uncoordinated contractions\n\n**Passenger (Fetus)**:\n- Size (macrosomia)\n- Presentation (breech, face, brow)\n- Position (OP \u2014 \"sunny side up\")\n- Multifetal pregnancy\n- Birth defects\n\n**Passage (Pelvis/Soft Tissues)**:\n- CPD\n- Contracted pelvis\n- Soft tissue resistance\n\n**Psyche (Psychological)**:\n- Lack of analgesic control of excessive pain\n- **Absence of a support person or coach**\n- **Immobility and restriction to bed**\n- **Inability to carry out cultural traditions**\n- **Anxiety causes hormone release that affects labor**\n\n### 15. Nursing Care for Abnormal Fetal Presentation/Position\n\nEncourage positions that favor fetal rotation and descent and reduce back pain:\n- Sitting, kneeling, or standing while leaning forward\n- Rocking pelvis back and forth on hands and knees\n- **Side-lying**\n- **Squatting** (second stage)\n- Lunging (one foot on chair, knee/foot pointed to that side)\n\n### 16. Multifetal Pregnancy\n\n**Challenges**:\n- Preterm labor risk\n- Malpresentation of one or more fetuses\n- Cord entanglement\n- Uterine overdistention \u2192 postpartum hemorrhage\n\n**Delivery**: Often requires C-section if first twin is not cephalic\n\n### 17. Preterm Labor \u2b50\n\n**Risk Factors**:\n- Previous preterm birth\n- Exposure to DES\n- Underweight\n- Chronic illness\n- Dehydration\n- Preeclampsia\n- Previous pregnancy losses\n- **Substance abuse**\n- **Chronic stress**\n- **Infection**\n- **Anemia**\n- Preterm PROM\n- **Inadequate prenatal care**\n- Poor nutrition\n- Low education level\n- **Poverty**\n- **Smoking**\n- **Multifetal pregnancy**\n\n**Maternal Symptoms**:\n- Contractions (uncomfortable or painless)\n- \"Balling up\" sensation\n- Menstrual-like cramps\n- **Constant low backache**\n- Pelvic pressure\n- Change in vaginal discharge\n- Abdominal cramps \u00b1 diarrhea\n- Vulva/thigh discomfort\n- \"Just feeling bad\" or \"coming down with something\"\n\n### 18. Fetal Fibronectin (fFN) Test\n\n**What it is**: A protein produced by fetal membranes\n\n**When tested**: 22-24 weeks\n\n**Interpretation**:\n- Present in vaginal secretions \u2192 predicts increased risk of PTL\n- Absent \u2192 low risk of PTL in next 1-2 weeks\n\n**Mechanism**: fFN helps keep amniotic sac attached to uterine lining; leaks into vaginal secretions if uterine activity, infection, or cervical effacement occurs\n\n### 19. Diagnosis of Preterm Labor\n\n- Cervical effacement and dilation of **more than 2 cm**\n- Shortened cervical length on ultrasound at 20 weeks (predictive)\n\n### 20. Tocolytic Therapy\n\n**Tocolytics**: Medications used to **stop or delay premature labor contractions**\n\n**Contraindications**:\n- Preeclampsia\n- Placenta previa\n- Abruptio placentae\n- Gestational age over 37 weeks\n- Chorioamnionitis\n- Fetal demise\n\n**Common Tocolytics**:\n\n| Drug | Mechanism | Key Nursing Points |\n|------|-----------|-------------------|\n| **Magnesium sulfate** | CNS depressant; relaxes smooth muscle | Monitor RR (>12), DTRs (absent = toxicity), urine output (>30 mL/hr); antidote = **calcium gluconate** |\n| **Terbutaline (Brethine)** | Beta-2 adrenergic agonist | Tachycardia, tremors, hyperglycemia, hypokalemia |\n| **Nifedipine (Procardia)** | Calcium channel blocker | \u2193 BP; monitor HR |\n\n**Nursing Care**:\n- Hydration\n- Check cultures (bacteria, GBS, possible SROM)\n- Fetal fibronectin\n- If PTB inevitable: give steroids for lung maturity\n\n### 21. Betamethasone for Fetal Lung Maturity\n\n**Purpose**: Accelerate fetal lung maturity before anticipated preterm delivery\n\n**Dosing**: 2 doses, **24 hours apart**, ideally **48 hours before** delivery\n\n**Alternative**: Dexamethasone (if betamethasone not available)\n\n### 22. Prolonged Pregnancy\n\n**Definition**: Pregnancy lasting longer than 40 weeks\n\n**Testing to confirm/monitor**:\n- **NST** (nonstress test)\n- **AFI** (amniotic fluid index)\n- **BPP** (biophysical profile) \u2014 score 8-10 normal, \u22646 concerning\n- **Kick counts**\n\n### 23. Obstetric Emergencies\n\n**Prolapsed Umbilical Cord**\n- Cord slips between presenting part and birth canal\n- **Types**: Complete (visible), Palpated (felt on exam), Occult (hidden, suspected by FHR)\n\n**Immediate Nursing Actions**:\n1. **Call for help immediately**\n2. **Knee-chest position** (or Trendelenburg/side-lying with hips elevated)\n3. **Insert gloved hand into vagina and push presenting part OFF cord**\n4. **Do not remove hand** until baby is delivered\n5. May need to ride on stretcher to OR and stay in position during C-section\n6. Administer **terbutaline** to stop contractions\n\n**Uterine Rupture**\n- **Complete**: Through all uterine layers\n- **Incomplete**: Through some layers\n- **Dehiscence**: Separation of old scar\n\n**Risk factors**: Prior C-section, trauma, hyperstimulation with oxytocin\n\n**Signs**: Sudden severe pain, hemorrhage, loss of contractions, fetal distress, maternal shock\n\n**Treatment**: Immediate C-section, blood products, possible hysterectomy\n\n**Amniotic Fluid Embolism (Anaphylactoid Syndrome)**\n- Amniotic fluid enters maternal circulation\n\n**Signs**: Sudden respiratory distress, cyanosis, cardiovascular collapse, DIC, seizures, coma\n\n**Treatment**:\n- Respiratory support (intubation, ventilation)\n- Treat shock with electrolytes and volume expanders\n- Replace coagulation factors (platelets, fibrinogen)\n- Monitor I/O, pulse ox\n- Likely ICU transfer\n\n---\n\n*This guide covers the major testable content from Chapters 6, 7, and 8. Focus especially on VEAL CHOP, stages of labor, Apgar scoring, Bishop score, induction contraindications, tocolytics, and emergency interventions.*\n";

window.studyGuideContent["ob_ch912_cheatsheet"] = "# OB Cheat Sheet: Postpartum & Newborn Care, Complications\n### Chapters 9, 10 & 12 — Quick Review\n\n---\n\n## 🤱 CHAPTER 9: THE FAMILY AFTER BIRTH\n\n### BUBBLE Postpartum Assessment ⭐\n| Letter | Assessment | Key Points |\n|--------|------------|------------|\n| **B** | Breasts | Soft/engorged; nipples intact |\n| **U** | Uterus | Firm, fundal height (↓1-2cm/day) |\n| **B** | Bladder | No distention |\n| **B** | Bowels | Gas, bowel sounds, stool |\n| **L** | Lochia | Rubra → Serosa → Alba |\n| **E** | Episiotomy/Perineum | REEDA |\n| **+E** | Emotions | Bonding, support |\n\n### Lochia Timeline\n| Type | Color | Duration |\n|------|-------|----------|\n| **Rubra** | 🔴 Red | Days 1-3 |\n| **Serosa** | 🟣 Pink | Days 4-10 |\n| **Alba** | ⚪ White | Days 10-21 |\n\n> Assess pads AND under patient — blood can overflow!\n\n### Uterine Involution\n- **1-2 cm/day** descent\n- **10 days**: No longer palpable\n- **5-6 weeks**: Back to pre-pregnant size\n- **Massage** if boggy!\n\n### Perineum Comfort\n| Time | Intervention |\n|------|--------------|\n| **First 12-24 hrs** | 🧊 Ice pack |\n| **After 24 hrs** | 🛁 Sitz bath |\n\n### Breastfeeding Hormones\n| Hormone | Source | Function |\n|---------|--------|----------|\n| **Prolactin** | Anterior pituitary | Milk **production** |\n| **Oxytocin** | Posterior pituitary | Let-down reflex (milk ejection) |\n\n**Contraindications**: HIV, HTLV-1 & 2\n\n### Milk Stages\n| Stage | Timing | Color/Notes |\n|-------|--------|-------------|\n| **Colostrum** | Days 1-3 | 🟡 Yellow, thick, immunoglobulins |\n| **Transitional** | Days 7-10 | ↑ Lactose |\n| **Mature** | Day 14+ | 🔵 Bluish, 20 kcal/oz |\n\n**Foremilk** = watery, thirst-quenching\n**Hindmilk** = fatty, satisfying\n\n### Newborn Heat Loss (4 Types)\n| Type | Cause | Prevention |\n|------|-------|------------|\n| **Evaporation** | Wet skin | Dry immediately |\n| **Conduction** | Cold surface | Warm blankets |\n| **Convection** | Drafts | Close doors, no fans |\n| **Radiation** | Cool objects | Radiant warmer, hat |\n\n### Newborn Hypoglycemia\n**<45 mg/dL** in term infant\n\n**Risks**: Preterm/postterm, diabetic mom, LGA/SGA, IUGR, cold stress\n\n**S/S**: Jittery, poor tone, sweating, high-pitched cry, seizures\n\n### Cord Care\n- Delayed clamping 30-60 sec\n- Keep **clean & dry**\n- Diaper below cord\n- Sponge bath until falls off\n\n---\n\n## 🚨 CHAPTER 10: POSTPARTUM COMPLICATIONS\n\n### Postpartum Hemorrhage (PPH) ⭐\n| Birth Type | PPH Threshold |\n|------------|---------------|\n| Vaginal | >500 mL |\n| C-Section | >1000 mL |\n\n**Timing**: Early (<24h) vs Late (24h-6wk)\n\n### 4 T's of PPH ⭐\n| Cause | Most Common | Treatment |\n|-------|-------------|-----------|\n| **Tone** | Uterine atony | Massage, oxytocin, Methergine |\n| **Trauma** | Lacerations | Surgical repair |\n| **Tissue** | Retained placenta | D&C |\n| **Thrombin** | Coagulopathy | Blood products, correct cause |\n\n### Atony vs. Laceration\n| Finding | Atony | Laceration |\n|---------|-------|------------|\n| Uterus | **Boggy** | Firm |\n| Bleeding | Dark red, clots | **Bright red**, trickle |\n| Fundus | High | Normal |\n\n### Hypovolemic Shock Signs\n> ⚠️ **Tachycardia FIRST** (before BP drops!)\n\n| Sign | Finding |\n|------|---------|\n| Pulse | ⬆️ Tachycardia |\n| BP | ⬇️ Hypotension |\n| Skin | Pale, cold, clammy |\n| Mental status | Altered |\n| Urine output | ⬇️ Decreased |\n\n### Thromboembolic Disorders\n| Type | Location | Key S/S |\n|------|----------|---------|\n| **SVT** | Superficial (saphenous) | Localized redness, warmth |\n| **DVT** | Deep (femoral) | Leg circumference >2cm diff, edema, pain |\n| **PE** | Pulmonary artery | Sudden chest pain, SOB, hemoptysis |\n\n**Prevention**: Early ambulation, SCDs, no popliteal pressure\n\n**Anticoagulant Teaching**:\n- Soft toothbrush\n- Report bleeding/bruising\n- Vitamin K = warfarin antidote\n- No LMWH with epidural\n\n### Puerperal Infection\n**Definition**: Fever ≥100.4°F (38°C) in first 24h AND ≥2 days in first 10 days\n\n**Most common**: **Endometritis**\n\n**Prevention**: Hand hygiene, front→back peripad\n\n### Mastitis\n**S/S**: Unilateral breast redness, warmth, pain + flu-like symptoms\n\n**Treatment** (5 cornerstones):\n1. ✅ Antibiotics\n2. ✅ **Continue breastfeeding/pumping**\n3. ✅ Analgesics\n4. ✅ Heat before feeding\n5. ✅ Cold after feeding\n\n> ⚠️ **Do NOT stop nursing** — worsens engorgement!\n\n### Postpartum Mood Disorders\n| Disorder | Onset | Duration | Severity |\n|----------|-------|----------|----------|\n| **Blues** | Days 2-3 | Resolves by day 10 | Mild, normal |\n| **Depression** | 2-4 weeks | Weeks-months | Moderate-severe |\n| **Psychosis** | <2 weeks | **Emergency!** | Severe — delusions, hallucinations |\n\n**Never assume \"just baby blues\"** — assess for persistence\n\n---\n\n## 👶 CHAPTER 12: THE TERM NEWBORN\n\n### Apgar Score ⭐\nScored at **1 and 5 minutes**\n\n| Sign | 0 | 1 | 2 |\n|------|---|---|---|\n| HR | Absent | <100 | >100 |\n| Resp | Absent | Slow | Good, cry |\n| Tone | Limp | Some flex | Active |\n| Reflex | None | Grimace | Cry |\n| Color | Blue/pale | Acrocyanosis | Pink |\n\n**7-10** = Normal | **4-6** = Moderate | **0-3** = Severe distress\n\n### Newborn Vital Signs\n| Parameter | Normal |\n|-----------|--------|\n| **Temp** | 97.1-99.8°F (36.2-37.7°C) |\n| **HR** | 110-160 bpm |\n| **RR** | 30-60/min |\n| **BP** | 60-80/40-50 |\n\n> Acrocyanosis (blue hands/feet) = normal!\n\n### Fontanelles\n| Type | Shape | Closes |\n|------|-------|--------|\n| **Anterior** | Diamond | ~18 months |\n| **Posterior** | Triangle | ~2-3 months |\n\n- **Bulging** = ↑ ICP\n- **Depressed** = Dehydration\n\n### Birth Injuries\n| Condition | Crosses Sutures? | Resolves |\n|-----------|------------------|----------|\n| **Molding** | N/A | Hours-days |\n| **Caput** | ✅ Yes | Days |\n| **Cephalohematoma** | ❌ No | Weeks |\n\n### Newborn Reflexes\n| Reflex | Disappears |\n|--------|------------|\n| **Rooting** | 3-4 mo |\n| **Sucking** | 4 mo |\n| **Moro** | 4-6 mo |\n| **Grasp** | 3-4 mo |\n| **Babinski** | 12 mo |\n| **Stepping** | 2 mo |\n| **Tonic Neck** | 4-6 mo |\n\n### Pain Scales\n- **FLACC** (Face, Legs, Activity, Cry, Consolability) — commonly used\n- **CRIES**, **NIPS**, **NPASS**\n\n### Newborn Nutrition\n| Stool | Appearance |\n|-------|------------|\n| **Meconium** | Black, tarry (first 24-48h) |\n| **Transitional** | Greenish-brown |\n| **Breastfed** | 🟡 Yellow, seedy, soft |\n| **Formula** | 🟤 Pale yellow/tan, firmer |\n\n**Vitamin D** commonly prescribed for breastfed infants\n\n### Danger Signs — Mother\n- Saturating >1 pad/hr\n- Foul-smelling lochia\n- Temp >100.4°F\n- Severe headache, vision changes\n- Chest pain, SOB\n- Leg swelling/redness\n- Thoughts of harming self/baby\n\n### Danger Signs — Newborn\n- Temp <97°F or >100.4°F\n- Grunting, retractions, cyanosis\n- Seizures, jitteriness\n- Poor feeding, lethargy\n- No wet diaper 12h / no stool 48h\n- Jaundice in first 24h\n- Cord redness, foul odor\n\n---\n\n## 📋 Memory Aids\n\n**BUBBLE** — Postpartum assessment\n**REEDA** — Perineum healing\n**4 T's** — PPH causes (Tone, Trauma, Tissue, Thrombin)\n\n---\n\n*Cheat Sheet for Chapters 9, 10 & 12 — Quick NCLEX Review*\n";

window.studyGuideContent["ob_ch912_comprehensive"] = "# Comprehensive Study Guide: Postpartum & Newborn Care, Complications\n### OB/Maternity Chapters 9, 10 & 12\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 9: The Family After Birth (Postpartum & Newborn Care)\n\n### 1. Puerperium (Postpartum Period)\n\nThe **puerperium** is the 6-week period after birth when the mother's body returns to its pre-pregnant state. Key postpartum factors:\n\n- Maternal/child pair vital sign stability\n- Control of postpartum bleeding to WNL\n- Establishment of newborn feeding\n\n### 2. BUBBLE Assessment\n\nPostpartum assessment follows the **BUBBLE** acronym:\n\n| Letter | Assessment | Key Findings |\n|--------|------------|--------------|\n| **B** | Breasts | Soft or engorged; check nipples for redness/cracking |\n| **U** | Uterus | Firmness, fundal height, location (1-2 cm/day involution) |\n| **B** | Bladder | Distention, voiding ability |\n| **B** | Bowels | Gas passage, bowel sounds, stool |\n| **L** | Lochia | Character, amount, color, odor, clots |\n| **E** | Episiotomy/Perineum | REEDA: Redness, Edema, Ecchymosis, Discharge, Approximation |\n\n**Additional E**: Emotions/bonding with newborn\n\n### 3. Vital Signs Postpartum\n\n- **Pulse**: Some bradycardia is common (50-70 bpm) due to decreased blood volume\n- **Respirations**: 12-20/min, should be stable\n- **Blood Pressure**: Should be stable; hypotension may indicate hemorrhage\n- **Temperature**: Slight elevation first 24 hrs is common; >100.4°F after 24 hrs = infection\n\n### 4. Uterine Involution\n\n**Involution** = return of uterus to non-pregnant state\n\n- Uterus reduces **1-2 cm per day**\n- By **10 days**: no longer palpable\n- By **5-6 weeks**: returns to pre-pregnant size\n- **Fundal height**: Immediately after birth at umbilicus; descends ~1 fingerbreadth/day\n\n**Massage the fundus** if boggy to stimulate contraction and prevent hemorrhage.\n\n### 5. Lochia (Vaginal Discharge)\n\n| Type | Color/Character | Duration |\n|------|-----------------|----------|\n| **Rubra** | Red, mostly blood | Up to 3 days |\n| **Serosa** | Pinkish, blood/mucus mix | Up to 10th day |\n| **Alba** | White/yellowish, mostly mucus | 10th-21st day |\n\n> ⚠️ Assess pads AND area under patient (underbed/chux) — blood can overflow beneath. Constant trickle of bright red lochia with firm fundus suggests laceration bleeding.\n\n### 6. Perineum & Vaginal Changes\n\n- **Rugae** (vaginal folds) disappear during birth; reappear by 3 weeks\n- Vagina never fully returns to pre-pregnant size\n- **Perineum**: Edematous, tender, bruised\n- **REEDA assessment** for perineal healing\n\n**Comfort Measures**:\n- **First 12-24 hrs**: Ice pack to perineum\n- **After 24 hrs**: Sitz bath (increases circulation, promotes healing)\n- Perineal care (peri bottle with warm water, front to back)\n\n### 7. Cesarean Section Adaptations\n\nSame as vaginal delivery PLUS:\n- Monitor abdominal dressing/incision\n- Lochia generally less\n- Urinary catheter care\n- Respiratory care (incentive spirometer)\n- Prevention of thrombophlebitis (SCDs, early ambulation)\n- Pain management (PCA, opioids)\n\n### 8. Breastfeeding & Lactation\n\n**Hormones**:\n- **Prolactin** (anterior pituitary): Milk production\n- **Oxytocin** (posterior pituitary): \"Let-down reflex\" (milk ejection) — tingling in breasts, uterine cramping\n\n**Contraindications to Breastfeeding**: HIV, HTLV-1 & 2 (transmitted via breast milk)\n\n**Milk Stages**:\n| Stage | Timing | Characteristics |\n|-------|--------|-----------------|\n| **Colostrum** | First few days | Yellowish, thicker; laxative effect; rich in immunoglobulins |\n| **Transitional** | 7-10 days | Increased lactose, fewer immunoglobulins |\n| **Mature** | By 14 days | Bluish; 20 kcal/oz; all needed nutrients |\n\n**Foremilk vs. Hindmilk**:\n- **Foremilk**: First milk; more watery, thirst-quenching\n- **Hindmilk**: Later milk; higher fat content; satisfies hunger\n\n**Feeding Schedule**: On demand, every 2-3 hrs for 15-30 min → 8-10 wet diapers/day + ≥1 stool\n\n**Galactagogues** (increase milk supply): Oatmeal, fenugreek, flaxseed, brewer's yeast\n\n**Storage**:\n- Room temp: 3 hrs\n- Refrigerator: 3 days\n- Freezer: 3 months\n\n### 9. Newborn Transition & Care (Ch. 9 Overview)\n\n**\"Golden Hour\"**: First hour after birth — baby stays with parents if ABCs stable; promotes bonding\n\n**Thermoregulation** (4 mechanisms of heat loss):\n| Mechanism | Description |\n|-----------|-------------|\n| **Evaporation** | Wet skin → dry |\n| **Conduction** | Contact with cold surface |\n| **Convection** | Drafts/air movement |\n| **Radiation** | Heat to cooler objects nearby |\n\n**Interventions**: Dry immediately, skin-to-skin, radiant warmer, hat, warm blankets\n\n### 10. Newborn Hypoglycemia\n\n**Definition**: Blood glucose <45 mg/dL in term infant\n\n**Risk Factors**:\n- Preterm or postterm\n- Diabetic mother\n- LGA or SGA\n- IUGR\n- Asphyxia\n- Cold stress\n- Tocolytics during labor\n\n**Signs/Symptoms**:\n- Jitteriness, poor muscle tone\n- Sweating, respiratory difficulty\n- Low temperature, poor suck\n- High-pitched cry, lethargy, seizures\n\n### 11. Cord Care\n\n- **Delayed clamping** (30-60 sec) → increased iron stores\n- Keep clean and dry\n- Fasten diaper below cord\n- Report: redness, moist, foul-smelling\n- Sponge bath until cord falls off (~1-2 weeks)\n\n### 12. Newborn Safety\n\n- **ID bands**: Match every time baby returned to parent\n- Place baby on **far side of bed** (away from door)\n- **Car seat**: Rear-facing until age 2; back seat; snug harness\n- **Never prop bottle** → choking, ear infections, tooth decay risk\n\n### 13. Discharge Teaching\n\n**Maternal Self-Care**:\n- Hygiene (peri care, front to back)\n- Sexual intercourse: Safe when bleeding stops + perineum healed (~6 weeks); use lubricant if breastfeeding\n- Diet & exercise\n- Danger signs to report\n\n**Newborn Discharge Care**:\n- Feeding cues\n- Safety (car seat, sleep position)\n- Follow-up appointments\n- Reassure: hospital staff available by phone\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 10: Nursing Care of Women with Complications After Birth\n\n### 1. Postpartum Hemorrhage (PPH)\n\n**Definition**:\n- Vaginal birth: >500 mL blood loss\n- C-section: >1000 mL blood loss\n\n**Timing**:\n- **Early (Primary)**: Within 24 hrs\n- **Late (Secondary)**: 24 hrs to 6 weeks\n\n**Leading cause of maternal mortality worldwide**\n\n### 2. Signs of Hypovolemic Shock\n\n> ⚠️ **Tachycardia is usually the FIRST sign** (before BP drops)\n\n| Sign | Finding |\n|------|---------|\n| Pulse | Tachycardia (rapid) |\n| BP | Falling systolic |\n| Skin | Pale, cold, clammy |\n| Mental status | Changes, confusion |\n| Urine output | Decreased |\n\n### 3. The 4 T's of PPH\n\n| Cause | Description |\n|-------|-------------|\n| **Tone** | Uterine atony (most common cause) |\n| **Trauma** | Lacerations, hematomas |\n| **Tissue** | Retained placental fragments |\n| **Thrombin** | Coagulopathy (DIC, eclampsia) |\n\n### 4. Uterine Atony\n\n**Definition**: Lack of normal muscle tone — uterus is \"boggy\" or soft\n\n**Assessment**:\n- Fundus difficult to feel\n- High fundal height (above umbilicus)\n- Excessive bleeding\n\n**Risk Factors**:\n- Overdistended uterus (polyhydramnios, large baby, multiple babies)\n- Prolonged labor, precipitous labor\n- Retained placenta\n- Full bladder\n- Grand multiparity\n- Precipitous delivery\n\n**Treatment**:\n- Fundal massage\n- Empty bladder\n- Medications: Oxytocin, methylergonovine (Methergine), prostaglandins (Hemabate, Misoprostol)\n\n### 5. Lacerations vs. Atony\n\n| Finding | Atony | Laceration |\n|---------|-------|------------|\n| Uterus | Boggy, hard to locate | Firm |\n| Bleeding | Dark red, with clots | **Bright red**, continuous trickle |\n| Treatment | Massage, oxytocin | Surgical repair |\n\n### 6. Hematomas\n\n**Causes**: Trauma during delivery (forceps, vacuum, episiotomy)\n\n**Signs**: Severe perineal pain, swelling, discoloration; may have difficulty voiding\n\n**Treatment**: Ice, analgesics, possible surgical evacuation if large\n\n### 7. Subinvolution\n\n**Definition**: Slower than expected return of uterus to non-pregnant state\n\n**Signs**:\n- Fundal height higher than expected\n- Persistent lochia rubra\n- Pelvic pain, heaviness, fatigue\n\n**Treatment**: Methergine, antibiotics, D&C if retained tissue\n\n### 8. Thromboembolic Disorders\n\n**Risk Factors** (Virchow's Triad):\n- Venous stasis (pregnancy)\n- Hypercoagulability (↑ fibrinogen, ↓ fibrinolysis)\n- Endothelial injury (delivery trauma)\n\n**Types**:\n| Type | Location | Key Findings |\n|------|----------|--------------|\n| **SVT** | Superficial veins (saphenous) | Localized redness, tenderness, warmth |\n| **DVT** | Deep veins (femoral, popliteal) | Leg circumference >2 cm difference, edema, pain, Homan's sign |\n| **PE** | Pulmonary artery | Sudden chest pain, dyspnea, cough, ↓ LOC, hemoptysis |\n\n**Prevention**:\n- Early ambulation\n- SCDs (sequential compression devices)\n- Avoid pressure behind knees (popliteal space)\n- Anti-embolic stockings\n\n**Treatment**:\n- SVT: Analgesics, heat, elevation\n- DVT: Heparin or LMWH (Lovenox), elevation\n- PE: ICU transfer, anticoagulation\n\n**Anticoagulant Teaching**:\n- Soft-bristled toothbrush (gum bleeding = excess anticoagulation)\n- Report: nosebleeds, unexplained bruising, prolonged bleeding\n- Vitamin K = antidote for warfarin overdose\n- LMWH contraindicated with regional anesthesia\n\n### 9. Puerperal Infection (Postpartum Sepsis)\n\n**Definition**: Fever ≥38°C (100.4°F) within first 24 hrs AND for ≥2 days during first 10 days postpartum\n\n**Risk Factors**:\n- Cracked nipples\n- Surgical incision (C-section, episiotomy)\n- Tissue trauma during labor\n- Retained placenta or blood clots\n- ↑ Vaginal pH after birth\n\n**Most common cause**: **Endometritis** (inflammation of uterine lining)\n\n**Prevention**:\n- Hand hygiene (primary means)\n- Front-to-back peripad application\n- Complete antibiotics as prescribed\n- Adequate rest and nutrition\n\n**Dangers**: Infection can ascend → uterus → fallopian tubes → peritonitis (life-threatening)\n\n### 10. Mastitis\n\n**Definition**: Infection of breast tissue (usually Staphylococcus aureus)\n\n**Signs**:\n- Unilateral breast redness, swelling, warmth, pain\n- Flu-like symptoms (fever, chills, body aches)\n\n**Treatment** (5 cornerstones):\n1. **Antibiotics** (dicloxacillin, cephalexin)\n2. **Milk removal** (continue breastfeeding or pumping — DO NOT stop)\n3. **Analgesics** prn\n4. **Heat before feeding** (warm compresses, shower)\n5. **Cold after feeding** (ice pack)\n\n> ⚠️ Weaning during mastitis worsens symptoms (engorgement/milk stasis)\n\n### 11. Postpartum Mood Disorders\n\n| Disorder | Onset | Duration | Characteristics |\n|----------|-------|----------|-----------------|\n| **Postpartum Blues (Baby Blues)** | Days 2-3 | Resolves by day 10 | Tearfulness, mood swings, anxiety — NORMAL, self-limiting |\n| **Postpartum Depression (PPD)** | Within 2-4 weeks | Weeks to months | Persistent sadness, lack of interest, guilt, sleep/appetite disturbance, inability to cope |\n| **Postpartum Psychosis** | Within 2 weeks | Medical emergency | Delusions, hallucinations, confusion, thoughts of harming self/baby |\n\n**Risk Factors for PPD**:\n- Inadequate social support\n- Poor relationship with partner\n- Life/childcare stress\n- Low self-esteem\n- Unplanned pregnancy\n- History of depression\n\n**Nursing Tip**: Never assume \"baby blues\" — assess for persistence and pervasiveness. Ask about suicidal/homicidal thoughts.\n\n**Treatment**:\n- Blues: Support, rest, reassurance\n- PPD: Psychotherapy, antidepressants (SSRIs safe in breastfeeding)\n- Psychosis: **Immediate psychiatric intervention**, antipsychotics, possible hospitalization\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 12: The Term Newborn\n\n### 1. Adjustment to Extrauterine Life\n\nNewborn adjustment depends on:\n- Genetic background\n- Health of uterine environment\n- Safe delivery\n- Care during first month\n\n### 2. Apgar Score ⭐\n\nStandardized evaluation at **1 and 5 minutes** after birth\n\n| Sign | 0 | 1 | 2 |\n|------|---|---|---|\n| **Heart Rate** | Absent | <100 bpm | >100 bpm |\n| **Respirations** | Absent | Slow, irregular | Good, crying |\n| **Muscle Tone** | Limp | Some flexion | Active motion |\n| **Reflexes** | No response | Grimace | Cry, cough, sneeze |\n| **Color** | Blue/pale | Acrocyanosis | Completely pink |\n\n**Score Interpretation**:\n- 7-10: Normal\n- 4-6: Moderate distress → assist\n- 0-3: Severe distress → immediate resuscitation\n\n### 3. Newborn Vital Signs\n\n| Parameter | Normal Range |\n|-----------|--------------|\n| **Temperature** | 36.2-37.7°C (97.1-99.8°F) |\n| **Heart Rate** | 110-160 bpm (may be higher first 30 min) |\n| **Respirations** | 30-60/min |\n| **Blood Pressure** | 60-80/40-50 mmHg |\n\n**Acrocyanosis** (blue hands/feet) is normal due to sluggish peripheral circulation — NOT central cyanosis\n\n### 4. Newborn Assessment\n\n**Head Circumference**: 32-36 cm (12.5-14.1 in); should not be >2 cm larger than chest\n\n**Fontanelles**:\n- **Anterior**: Diamond-shaped; closes ~18 months\n- **Posterior**: Triangular; closes ~2-3 months\n- **Flat** = normal; **Bulging** = ↑ ICP; **Depressed** = dehydration\n\n**Birth Injuries**:\n| Condition | Description | Crosses Suture Lines? |\n|-----------|-------------|----------------------|\n| **Molding** | Overlapping skull bones from birth canal | N/A |\n| **Caput Succedaneum** | Swelling of scalp soft tissues | **Yes** |\n| **Cephalohematoma** | Bleeding beneath periosteum | **No** |\n\n> Caput resolves in days; cephalohematoma may take weeks\n\n### 5. Newborn Reflexes\n\n| Reflex | Description | Disappears |\n|--------|-------------|------------|\n| **Rooting** | Turns head toward touch on cheek | 3-4 months |\n| **Sucking** | Sucks when nipple/pacifier touches lips | 4 months (voluntary) |\n| **Moro (Startle)** | Arms extend then adduct when startled | 4-6 months |\n| **Grasp (Palmar)** | Fingers curl around object in palm | 3-4 months |\n| **Babinski** | Toes fan out when sole stroked | 1 year |\n| **Stepping** | \"Walking\" motions when held upright | 2 months |\n| **Tonic Neck (Fencing)** | Head turned → arm extends on that side | 4-6 months |\n\n### 6. Pain Assessment in Newborns\n\nUse validated scales:\n- **CRIES**: Crying, Requires O₂, ↑ vital signs, Expression, Sleeplessness (10 pt)\n- **FLACC**: Face, Legs, Activity, Cry, Consolability (10 pt) — commonly used\n- **NIPS**: Neonatal Infant Pain Scale\n- **NPASS**: Neonatal Pain, Agitation, Sedation Scale (most common)\n\n### 7. Thermoregulation\n\nNewborn cannot regulate temperature well:\n- **Sweat glands don't function** → risk of overheating\n- Cold stress → ↑ O₂ consumption, ↓ glucose, acidosis\n\n**Maintain**:\n- Dry immediately after birth\n- Skin-to-skin contact\n- Radiant warmer\n- Hat, warm blankets\n\n### 8. Newborn Nutrition\n\n**Meconium**: First stool (black, tarry) — passed within 24-48 hrs\n**Transitional stool**: Greenish-brown\n**Breastfed stool**: Yellow, seedy, soft\n**Formula-fed stool**: Pale yellow/tan, firmer\n\n**Feeding increases gradually** with growth\n\n**Vitamins**:\n- **Vitamin D**: Commonly prescribed (breastfed infants at risk for deficiency)\n- Vitamin K: Given IM at birth to prevent hemorrhagic disease\n\n### 9. Infection Prevention\n\nNewborn immune system is immature:\n- **Hand hygiene** = primary prevention\n- Umbilical cord stump = primary infection site if not kept clean\n- Avoid sick contacts\n- Proper handwashing before handling\n\n### 10. Discharge Planning & Parent Teaching\n\n**Key Teaching Topics**:\n- Feeding cues and techniques\n- Sleep safety (back to sleep, firm mattress)\n- Cord care\n- Circumcision care (if applicable)\n- Bathing (sponge until cord falls off)\n- Car seat safety\n- Signs of illness to report\n- Follow-up pediatrician appointment (within 48-72 hrs if discharged <48 hrs)\n\n**Infant Abduction Prevention**:\n- ID bands checked every time\n- Never leave baby alone in room\n- Educate parents about security\n\n---\n\n## Quick Reference: Danger Signs to Report\n\n### Mother\n- Heavy bleeding (saturating >1 pad/hr)\n- Foul-smelling lochia\n- Fever >100.4°F\n- Severe headache, vision changes (preeclampsia signs)\n- Chest pain, shortness of breath\n- Leg swelling/redness/pain (DVT)\n- Feelings of harming self or baby\n\n### Newborn\n- Temperature <97°F or >100.4°F\n- Difficulty breathing, grunting, retractions\n- Cyanosis (central)\n- Seizures, jitteriness\n- Poor feeding, lethargy\n- No wet diaper in 12 hrs or no stool in 48 hrs\n- Yellow skin (jaundice) in first 24 hrs\n- Cord redness, foul odor, bleeding\n\n---\n\n*Study Guide for Chapters 9, 10 & 12 — OB/Maternity*\n*Based on course content and NCLEX-relevant material*\n";

window.studyGuideContent["peds_quiz1_ch15_19"] = "# PEDS Quiz 1 Review — Comprehensive Study Guide\n### Chapters 15-19: Growth, Development & Nutrition | Infant | Toddler | Preschool | School-Age\n**Exam Focus: Pediatric Nursing — First Exam**\n\n---\n\n## 📊 CHAPTER 15: OVERVIEW OF GROWTH, DEVELOPMENT, AND NUTRITION\n\n### Growth vs. Development\n| Term | Definition |\n|------|------------|\n| **Growth** | Measurable changes (height, weight, head circumference) |\n| **Development** | Qualitative changes in skills, behaviors, cognition |\n\n- Growth spurts followed by plateaus\n- Not all parts mature at same time\n- Children differ from adults in anatomy/physiology — illnesses present differently\n\n### Developmental Theories\n\n#### Erikson's Psychosocial Stages\n| Stage | Age | Crisis | Key Task |\n|-------|-----|--------|----------|\n| Trust vs. Mistrust | 0-1 yr | Trust | Consistent care builds trust |\n| Autonomy vs. Shame/Doubt | 1-3 yr | Autonomy | Independence, toilet training |\n| Initiative vs. Guilt | 3-6 yr | Initiative | Purposeful play, curiosity |\n| Industry vs. Inferiority | 6-12 yr | Industry | Competence, school achievement |\n\n#### Piaget's Cognitive Stages\n| Stage | Age | Key Feature |\n|-------|-----|-------------|\n| **Sensorimotor** | 0-2 yr | Object permanence, reflexes → intentional actions |\n| **Preoperational** | 2-7 yr | Egocentrism, magical thinking, symbolic play |\n| **Concrete Operational** | 7-11 yr | Logical thinking, conservation, classification |\n| **Formal Operational** | 11+ yr | Abstract reasoning, hypothetical thinking |\n\n#### Kohlberg's Moral Development\n| Level | Age | Focus |\n|-------|-----|-------|\n| Preconventional | <9 yr | Punishment/reward |\n| Conventional | 9-13 yr | Social approval, rules |\n| Postconventional | 13+ yr | Abstract principles, justice |\n\n### Denver Developmental Screening Test\n- Assesses: Personal-social, Fine motor-adaptive, Language, Gross motor\n- Purpose: Identify children NOT performing at age-appropriate level\n- NOT an intelligence test\n\n### Nutrition Basics\n- **Newborn GI**: Immature first 3 months — saliva minimal, relies on HCl/rennin/trypsin\n- Fat/cholesterol NOT restricted in infants (needed for CNS development)\n- **Childhood Obesity**: Rising post-pandemic — screen BMI, counsel family\n\n### Dental Health\n- First tooth erupts ~6 months\n- **Baby bottle caries**: Milk/juice pools in mouth during sleep — most common 18mo-3yr\n- **Education**: Brush after each meal/snack, replace brush every 3 months\n- Sticky foods (gum, dried fruit, cake, candy) → more caries than sugared drinks\n- Recommended snacks: cheese, milk, raw vegetables, sugarless gum\n- **Teething**: Fever NOT associated — assess for other causes\n\n### Play\n- Play is the \"work\" of childhood — essential for development\n- Types: Solitary → Parallel → Cooperative (age-dependent)\n\n---\n\n## 👶 CHAPTER 16: THE INFANT (0-12 MONTHS)\n\n### Milestones by Age\n| Age | Key Milestones |\n|-----|----------------|\n| **1-3 mo** | Social smile, lifts head prone, follows objects |\n| **2-6 mo** | Rolls over, reaches for objects, sits with support |\n| **3-10 mo** | Sits alone (6mo), pincer grasp developing, stranger anxiety |\n| **10-12 mo** | Pulls to stand, cruises, says \"mama/dada\", walks with assistance |\n\n> ⚠️ **6-month checkup**: If child CANNOT sit independently → developmental concern\n> ⚠️ **10-month**: Should walk when led/held — if not, assess motor delay\n\n### Erikson: Trust vs. Mistrust (0-1yr)\n- Trust built through consistent, loving care\n- Mistrust develops if needs not met\n\n### Piaget: Sensorimotor Stage (0-2yr)\n- Object permanence develops ~8-9 months\n- Cause and effect learning\n\n### Nutrition\n- Breast milk or formula only for first 6 months\n- Introduce solids ~6 months (iron-fortified cereal first)\n- No honey until 12 months (botulism risk)\n- No cow's milk until 12 months\n\n---\n\n## 🧸 CHAPTER 17: THE TODDLER (1-3 YEARS)\n\n### Milestones by Age\n| Age | Key Milestones |\n|-----|----------------|\n| **12-15 mo** | Walks independently, says 3-5 words |\n| **18 mo** | Climbs stairs with help, 10-20 word vocabulary |\n| **24 mo** | Runs, jumps, 2-3 word sentences, knows ~50 words |\n| **36 mo** | Pedals tricycle, copies circle, knows colors |\n\n### Erikson: Autonomy vs. Shame/Doubt (1-3yr)\n- \"No!\" phase — normal assertion of independence\n- Toilet training: Readiness ~18-24 months\n\n### Piaget: Preoperational Stage (2-7yr)\n- Magical thinking, egocentrism\n- Symbolic play\n\n### Common Issues\n- **Temper tantrums**: Normal; ignore or redirect\n- **Negativism**: \"No!\" — offer choices\n- **Regression**: Common during stress/illness\n\n---\n\n## 👦 CHAPTER 18: THE PRESCHOOL CHILD (3-5 YEARS)\n\n### Milestones\n- Speaks in full sentences\n- Copies shapes, draws person with 3+ parts\n- Cooperative play (shared rules)\n- Imaginary friends common\n\n### Erikson: Initiative vs. Guilt (3-6yr)\n- Takes initiative in activities\n- Guilt if made to feel bad about efforts\n\n### Piaget: Preoperational (continued)\n- Animism (objects have feelings)\n- Centration (focus on one aspect)\n\n### Moral Development (Kohlberg: Preconventional)\n- Right/wrong based on reward/punishment\n\n---\n\n## 🏫 CHAPTER 19: THE SCHOOL-AGE CHILD (6-12 YEARS)\n\n### Milestones\n- Reads fluently, writes legibly\n- Concrete operational thinking (Piaget)\n- Industry vs. Inferiority (Erikson)\n- Peer relationships critical\n\n### Erikson: Industry vs. Inferiority (6-12yr)\n- Sense of competence from school achievement\n- Inferiority if repeated failures\n\n### Piaget: Concrete Operational (7-11yr)\n- Logical thinking about concrete objects\n- Conservation, classification, seriation\n\n### Health & Safety\n- Bike helmet, seat belt\n- Stranger danger education\n- Screen time limits\n\n---\n\n*Study Guide for Chapters 15-19 — Pediatric Nursing*\n";

window.studyGuideContent["peds_quiz2_ch20_24"] = "# PEDS Quiz 2 Review — Comprehensive Study Guide\n### Chapters 20-24: Adolescent | Hospitalization | Health Care Adaptations | Neuro & Sensory | Musculoskeletal\n**Exam Focus: PED — Disorders and Diseases of Infants, Toddlers, and School Age**\n\n---\n\n## 📊 CHAPTER 20: THE ADOLESCENT\n\n### Physical Development\n| Concept | Details |\n|---------|---------|\n| **Puberty** | Period of rapid reproductive maturation; begins with secondary sex characteristics, ends with mature sperm/regular menses |\n| **Growth Spurt** | Final 20% of adult height; girls mature 6mo–2yr before boys |\n| **Asynchrony** | Body parts mature at different rates → awkward, gangly appearance |\n| **Tanner Stages** | Used to assess sexual maturity |\n\n#### Boys (10-13yr onset)\n- Voice deepens, hair growth (face, chest, axillae, pubic)\n- Testicular enlargement → penile enlargement\n- **Teach**: Monthly testicular self-exam\n\n#### Girls\n- Breast development, menarche (10-15yr)\n- **Teach**: Monthly breast self-exam\n\n#### Skin & Acne\n- Active sweat glands → oily skin, acne common\n- Teach gentle cleansing, avoid picking, OTC treatments\n\n### Psychosocial Development\n#### Erikson: Identity vs. Role Confusion\n- Major task: Establish identity, separate from family, initiate intimacy\n- **Emancipation**: Critical for developing individuality\n- May reject childhood self and family; question parental values\n- Disagreements common around: dating, car, money, grades, friends, smoking, sex, drugs\n\n#### Piaget: Formal Operational Stage\n- Abstract reasoning, hypothetical thinking\n- Can understand symbols, religious concepts beyond family tradition\n\n#### Freud: Genital Stage\n- Focus on mature sexual relationships\n\n### Key Developmental Tasks\n- Establishing identity\n- Separating from family\n- Initiating intimacy\n- Developing career choices for economic independence\n\n### Common Adolescent Issues (Nursing Focus)\n| Issue | Nursing Interventions |\n|-------|----------------------|\n| Body image disturbance | Reinforce healthy self-concept; educate on normal variations |\n| Risk-taking behavior | Safety education (seat belts, helmet, STI prevention, substance use) |\n| Peer pressure | Teach refusal skills, assertiveness |\n| Eating disorders | Screen for anorexia/bulimia; assess body image, eating patterns |\n| Depression/suicide | Screen; assess for hopelessness; refer immediately if suicidal ideation |\n\n### Sexual Health\n- STI prevention education (condoms, abstinence)\n- Contraception counseling (confidentiality, parental notification laws vary)\n- Pregnancy prevention\n\n### Cultural/Spiritual Considerations\n- Adolescents explore family values and may embrace or separate from them\n- Exposure to other religions/practices helps stabilize group identity\n\n---\n\n## 🏥 CHAPTER 21: THE CHILD'S EXPERIENCE OF HOSPITALIZATION\n\n### Health Care Delivery Settings\n- Acute care hospital\n- Extended/long-term care facility\n- Urgent care center\n- Outpatient clinic/office\n- Pediatric research center\n- Outpatient surgery center\n- Home care\n\n### Separation Anxiety (6 months+; most pronounced in toddlers)\n| Stage | Behavior | Nursing Interventions |\n|-------|----------|----------------------|\n| **Protest** | Loud crying, calls for parent, watches/listens for them | Allow parent to stay; provide comfort items |\n| **Despair** | Sad, depressed, withdrawn; less active play | Encourage parent presence; therapeutic play |\n| **Denial/Detachment** | Appears to deny need for parent; detached, uninterested in visits | Prepare parents; encourage frequent visits |\n\n### Age-Specific Reactions to Hospitalization\n\n#### Infants\n- Stranger anxiety peaks; maintain routines\n- Prepare: Provide comfort objects, parental presence\n\n#### Toddlers/Preschoolers\n- Separation anxiety most intense\n- Magical thinking → may believe illness is punishment\n- Prepare: Use simple terms, allow choices, demonstrate equipment\n\n#### School-Age Children\n- Need control and understanding\n- Allow to examine/play with equipment\n- Prepare: Explain procedures honestly; offer rewards\n\n#### Adolescents\n- Privacy is critical\n- Involve in decisions\n- Prepare: Discuss coping techniques; provide privacy\n\n### Preparation for Procedures (Box 21.1 pg. 480)\n- Tailor to developmental stage\n- Use simple, honest language\n- Offer choices when possible\n- Provide distraction (bubbles, toys, videos)\n- Allow play with equipment before use\n- Reward after procedure\n\n### Therapeutic Play\n- Reduces anxiety and fear\n- Types: Medical play (doll with IV), expressive play (drawing feelings)\n- Helps children process hospitalization experience\n\n### Family-Centered Care\n- Parents are partners in care\n- Assess parental stress; provide support\n- Educate parents on their role in child's care\n- Allow parents to stay overnight when possible\n\n---\n\n## 🩺 CHAPTER 22: HEALTH CARE ADAPTATIONS FOR THE CHILD AND FAMILY\n\n### Admission to Pediatric Unit — Nursing Responsibilities\n- Obtain informed consent (parent/guardian; child assent if age-appropriate)\n- Orient child and family to unit\n- Establish rapport and trust\n\n### Basic Data Collection\n| Component | Details |\n|-----------|---------|\n| **Observation** | Level of interaction, behavior, affect |\n| **Growth & Development** | Compare to age norms (height, weight, head circ) |\n| **History Survey** | Chief complaint, past medical history, immunizations, family history |\n| **Pain Assessment** | Use age-appropriate scale (FLACC, FACES, numeric) |\n\n### Physical Survey\n- Vital signs (age-specific normal ranges)\n- Weight (infants in grams)\n- Height\n- Head circumference (infants until 2-3yr)\n- Pain level\n\n### Specimen Collection\n1. Verify physician order\n2. Obtain lab requisitions, correct containers, supplies\n3. Collect specimen (age-appropriate technique)\n4. Label clearly with patient ID\n5. Send to lab per policy\n6. Document in notes and I&O record\n\n### Medication Administration in Infants & Children\n| Factor | Consideration |\n|--------|---------------|\n| **Absorption** | Oral: Stomach pH higher in infants; IM: Smaller muscle mass |\n| **Metabolism** | Liver immature; slower drug metabolism |\n| **Excretion** | Kidneys immature; longer half-life |\n| **Age** | MOST IMPORTANT variable in predicting drug response |\n\n#### Nursing Responsibilities\n- **ALWAYS** calculate safe dose before administration\n- Observe for toxic symptoms\n- Routes: Oral (use oral syringe, never household spoon), Parenteral (small needles), IV (microdrip, careful rate), TPN (total parenteral nutrition)\n\n### Pain Management\n- Use age-appropriate assessment tools\n- Pharmacologic: Acetaminophen, ibuprofen, opioids (weight-based dosing)\n- Non-pharmacologic: Distraction, positioning, comfort measures, parental presence\n\n---\n\n## 👂👁 CHAPTER 23: THE CHILD WITH A SENSORY OR NEUROLOGICAL CONDITION\n\n### Ear Anatomy Differences (Newborn vs Adult)\n| Feature | Newborn | Adult |\n|---------|---------|-------|\n| Tympanic membrane | Almost horizontal | Angled |\n| Vascularity | More vascular | Less |\n| Light reflex | Inconsistent | Clear |\n| Eustachian tube | Shorter, straighter | Longer, angled |\n\n#### Eustachian Tube Functions\n- Ventilation (equalizes pressure)\n- Protection (from nasopharyngeal secretions)\n- Drainage (middle ear secretions)\n\n### Otitis Externa (Swimmer's Ear)\n- Acute infection of external canal\n- **Signs**: Pain/tenderness on pinna/tragus manipulation; tympanic membrane normal\n- **Treatment**: Irrigation + topical antibiotics/antivirals\n- **Nursing**: Insert wick after drops if canal swollen\n\n### Acute Otitis Media (AOM)\n- Inflammation of middle ear\n- **Cause**: Often follows URI; *S. pneumoniae*, *H. influenzae*\n- **Risk**: Infants more prone due to anatomy; immature immunity\n- **Signs**: Fever, irritability, pulling at ear, decreased hearing\n- **Treatment**: Antibiotics (amoxicillin first-line), analgesics, decongestants\n\n#### Nursing Care\n- Instill ear drops correctly: **Infants** — pull pinna DOWN and BACK; **Children** — pull pinna UP and BACK\n- Teach completion of full antibiotic course\n- Follow-up in 48-72hr if not improving\n\n### Hearing Impairment\n- **Causes**: Congenital (TORCH infections, genetic), acquired (ototoxic drugs, meningitis, chronic OM)\n- **Assessment**: Newborn hearing screening; observe for response to sound\n- **Nursing**:\n  - Face child when speaking; use visual cues\n  - Speak clearly, normal volume\n  - Use sign language/interpreter if appropriate\n  - Encourage cochlear implant or hearing aids as indicated\n\n### Eye Disorders\n\n#### Strabismus (Crossed Eyes)\n- Misalignment of eyes; constant or intermittent\n- **Types**: Paralytic (nerve/muscle) vs Nonparalytic (refractive)\n- **Treatment**: Patching good eye (to strengthen weak eye), corrective lenses, surgery if needed\n- **Complication**: Amblyopia if untreated\n\n#### Amblyopia (Lazy Eye)\n- Reduced vision in one eye from disuse\n- **Treatment**: Patch stronger eye to force use of weaker eye\n\n#### Prevention of Eyestrain\n- Proper lighting, reading distance\n- Limit screen time\n- Annual vision screening\n\n### Seizure Disorders\n- **Febrile seizures**: Most common in children 6mo-5yr; brief, generalized; usually benign\n- **Epilepsy**: Recurrent unprovoked seizures\n- **Nursing during seizure**:\n  - Protect from injury (clear area, side-lying)\n  - Time seizure; do NOT restrain\n  - Do NOT put anything in mouth\n  - Suction if needed; administer oxygen\n  - Administer rescue meds (rectal diazepam) if ordered\n  - Postictal: Position for airway; monitor vitals\n\n---\n\n## 🦴 CHAPTER 24: THE CHILD WITH A MUSCULOSKELETAL CONDITION\n\n### Characteristics of Child's Musculoskeletal System\n| Feature | Implication |\n|---------|-------------|\n| Bone not fully ossified | More porous; fractures heal faster |\n| Epiphyses present | Growth plates; bone overgrowth common after fracture in <10yr |\n| Periosteum thick | Produces callus rapidly; better healing |\n| Lower mineral content | Bones stronger despite porosity |\n\n### Musculoskeletal Assessment\n- **Observation**: Gait, posture, muscle tone, symmetry\n- **Palpation**: Tenderness, swelling, warmth\n- **ROM**: Passive and active\n- **Gait Assessment**:\n  - Toddler: Wide, unstable gait; arms don't swing\n  - By 18mo: Base narrows, more stable\n  - By 4yr: Can hop on one foot\n  - By 6yr: Adult-like gait\n- ⚠️ Child not walking by 18mo → refer for evaluation\n\n### Common Disorders\n\n#### Fractures\n- **Greenstick**: Incomplete fracture (one side bends, other breaks) — common in children\n- **Buckle/torus**: Compression fracture\n- **Healing**: Faster than adults due to active periosteum\n\n#### Legg-Calvé-Perthes Disease\n- Avascular necrosis of femoral head\n- **Age**: 4-10yr; boys > girls\n- **Signs**: Limp, hip pain, limited ROM\n- **Treatment**: Rest, bracing, surgery if severe\n\n#### Slipped Capital Femoral Epiphysis (SCFE)\n- Femoral head slips at growth plate\n- **Age**: 10-16yr; overweight adolescents at higher risk\n- **Signs**: Hip/knee pain, limp, external rotation of leg\n- **Treatment**: Surgical pinning\n\n#### Developmental Dysplasia of the Hip (DDH)\n- Abnormal hip development\n- **Assessment**: Ortolani/Barlow maneuvers in infants\n- **Treatment**: Pavlik harness (newborns), hip spica cast (older infants)\n\n#### Scoliosis\n- Lateral curvature of spine\n- **Screening**: Adams forward bend test\n- **Treatment**: Observation, bracing (Boston brace), surgery if severe (>40-50°)\n\n### Treatments\n\n#### Cast Care\n- Elevate limb first 24-48hr\n- Neurovascular checks: color, temp, cap refill, sensation, movement\n- Keep dry; no foreign objects inside\n- Report: increased pain, swelling, numbness, foul odor\n\n#### Traction\n- **Skin traction**: Buck's, Russell's — temporary\n- **Skeletal traction**: Pins through bone — longer-term\n- **Nursing**: Weights hanging freely, ropes aligned, countertraction maintained\n\n#### Bracing\n- Used for scoliosis, clubfoot, DDH\n- Teach skin care, proper fit, wear schedule\n\n### Common Nursing Interventions\n| Situation | Intervention |\n|-----------|--------------|\n| Fracture with cast | Elevate, ice, neurovascular checks q1-2hr |\n| Post-op DDH/SCFE | Position per orders; pain management; PT referral |\n| Scoliosis brace | Ensure correct fit; skin checks; encourage compliance |\n| Muscular dystrophy | Supportive care; respiratory monitoring; mobility aids |\n\n---\n\n## 📋 QUICK REFERENCE: COMMON PEDS CONDITIONS CH20-24\n\n| Condition | Chapter | Key Points |\n|-----------|---------|------------|\n| Acne | 20 | Common in adolescence; teach gentle cleansing |\n| Identity crisis | 20 | Erikson: Identity vs Role Confusion |\n| Separation anxiety | 21 | 3 stages: Protest → Despair → Denial |\n| Otitis media | 23 | Most common in infants; pull pinna DOWN/BACK for drops |\n| Strabismus | 23 | Patching; prevent amblyopia |\n| Febrile seizures | 23 | Common 6mo-5yr; usually benign |\n| Greenstick fracture | 24 | Incomplete; heals faster than adult |\n| Scoliosis | 24 | Screen with Adams test; brace if 20-40° |\n\n---\n\n## 🎯 KEY NURSING CONCEPTS (Cross-Chapter)\n\n### Developmental Considerations\n- Always consider child's developmental stage when planning care\n- Age-appropriate communication and preparation\n- Involve parents/family in care decisions\n\n### Safety\n- Car seats, bike helmets, water safety (adolescents: driving, drowning)\n- Medication safety (childproof caps, storage)\n- Fall prevention (cribs, high chairs, hospital beds)\n\n### Family-Centered Care\n- Parents are experts on their child\n- Provide emotional support and education\n- Encourage parental presence during procedures\n\n### Pain Management\n- Use age-appropriate tools\n- Combine pharmacologic + non-pharmacologic approaches\n- Reassess after interventions\n\n---\n\n**Exam Next Friday — Good Luck!**  \nStudy tip: Review rationales in the peds exam modules (Ch 20-24) in the app for practice questions.\n";

window.studyGuideContent["quiz3_upper_gi"] = "# \ud83e\ude7a Quiz 3 Study Guide: Upper GI Disorders & Meds\n\n> [!TIP]\n> This guide focuses strictly on **Upper GI** conditions and pharmacology as requested for Quiz 3. It synthesizes the `MSQ3 Upper GI and Meds.docx` and the `GI Upper` / `GI Drugs` lectures.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Oral & Esophageal Conditions\n\n### Thrush (Oral Candidiasis)\n- **Patho:** Caused by *Candida albicans* (fungus).\n- **Presentation:** White/bluish-white patches on oral mucous membranes.\n- **Risks:** Immunocompromised, prolonged antibiotic use.\n- **Treatment:** Local or systemic antifungals.\n\n### Mucositis vs. Stomatitis vs. Gastritis\n- **Mucositis:** Inflammation/ulceration of mucous membranes (mouth \u2192 GI tract).\n  - *Treatment:* Viscous lidocaine to numb mucosa. **Nursing Priority:** Avoid eating for 30 mins after use (Aspiration Risk!).\n- **Stomatitis:** Inflammation localized to the oral cavity.\n- **Gastritis:** Stomach lining inflammation causing epigastric pain, nausea, and possible hematemesis.\n\n### Oral & Esophageal Cancer\n- **Oral Cancer Risks:** Tobacco, excessive alcohol, chronic gum disease.\n  - *Nursing Priority:* Maintain airway; keep oral suction equipment available.\n- **Esophageal Cancer Key Sign:** Progressive dysphagia (difficulty swallowing). Starts with solid foods, progresses to liquids.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Esophageal Disorders (GERD & Hernia)\n\n### GERD (Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease)\n- **Patho:** Decreased lower esophageal sphincter (LES) tone allows stomach acid/pepsin to reflux into the esophagus.\n- **Symptoms:** Heartburn, regurgitation.\n  - *Critical Assessment:* Treat heartburn symptoms as cardiac disease until myocardial infarction is ruled out!\n- **Nursing & Lifestyle Management:**\n  - Avoid eating 2\u20133 hours before bedtime.\n  - Avoid triggers (caffeine, chocolate, fatty foods, citrus, spicy foods).\n  - Small, frequent meals.\n  - Remain upright after eating.\n\n### Hiatal Hernia\n- **Patho:** Protrusion of the stomach upward through the diaphragm.\n- **Symptoms:** Heartburn, regurgitation (very similar to GERD).\n- **Management:** Same as GERD; avoid lying down after meals.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Gastric and Duodenal Disorders\n\n### Peptic Ulcer Disease (PUD)\n- **Risk Factors:** Long-term NSAID use (ibuprofen), smoking, *Helicobacter pylori* infection.\n- **Symptoms:** Burning, gnawing, aching stomach pain.\n\n### Gastric vs. Duodenal Ulcers\n| Feature | Gastric Ulcers | Duodenal Ulcers |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Pain Timing** | Worse *with* meals | 2\u20133 hours *after* meals, **relieved by food** |\n| **Primary Cause** | NSAIDs / mucosal damage | *H. pylori* infection |\n| **Weight Change** | Weight loss | Weight gain |\n| **Bleeding Pattern** | Hematemesis (vomiting blood) | Melena (black tarry stools) |\n\n> [!WARNING]\n> **Perforation is a Medical Emergency! (Peritonitis)**\n> - Sudden, severe abdominal pain\n> - Rigid, board-like abdomen\n> - Tachycardia & Hypotension\n> - Absent bowel sounds\n\n### Esophageal Varices\n- **Patho:** Swollen, fragile blood vessels in the esophagus (usually due to portal hypertension).\n- **Signs of Rupture:** Melena, hypotension, tachycardia. Life-threatening bleeding risk!\n- **Intervention:** Urgent EGD (Endoscopy). Patient must remain NPO post-procedure until gag reflex returns.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Upper GI Pharmacology\n\n### \ud83d\udc8a Proton Pump Inhibitors (PPIs)\n- **Examples:** Omeprazole (Prilosec), Pantoprazole (Protonix), Esomeprazole (Nexium).\n- **Action:** Inhibit gastric acid secretion at the parietal cell pump.\n- **Nursing:** Take before meals (morning, empty stomach).\n\n### \ud83d\udc8a H2 Receptor Blockers\n- **Examples:** Famotidine, Cimetidine.\n- **Action:** Block H2 receptors to reduce acid secretion volume.\n\n### \ud83d\udc8a Antacids\n- **Action:** Neutralize gastric acid.\n- **Side Effects:** \n  - Magnesium = Diarrhea\n  - Aluminum/Calcium = Constipation\n\n### \ud83d\udc8a Mucosal Protectants (Coating Agents)\n- **Example:** Sucralfate (Carafate).\n- **Action:** Forms a thick protective coating over ulcers. Does *not* reduce acid.\n- **Nursing:** Give on an empty stomach.\n\n### \ud83d\udc8a Gastrointestinal Prostaglandins\n- **Example:** Misoprostol (Cytotec).\n- **Use:** Prevent gastric ulcers caused by NSAIDs.\n- **Contraindication:** **Pregnancy** (Causes miscarriage/uterine contractions).\n\n### \ud83d\udc8a Prokinetic Agents\n- **Example:** Metoclopramide (Reglan).\n- **Action:** Increases gastric motility and speeds emptying.\n- **Risk:** Extrapyramidal symptoms (EPS) - twitching, facial grimacing.\n\n### \ud83d\udc8a H. Pylori Treatment\n- **Triple Therapy:** Two antibiotics + One PPI. Patient must complete the full antibiotic course.\n\n### \ud83d\udc8a Antiemetics (Nausea/Vomiting)\n- **Serotonin Antagonists:** Ondansetron (Zofran).\n- **Chemotherapy Nursing (CINV):** Administer 30-60 mins *before* chemo, continue 1-2 days after.\n";
window.studyGuideContent["quiz4_lower_gi"] = "# \ud83e\ude7a Quiz 4 Study Guide: Lower GI Disorders & Meds\n\n> [!TIP]\n> This guide focuses strictly on **Lower GI** conditions, bowel elimination, and pharmacology as requested for Quiz 4. It synthesizes data from the `GI Lower` and `GI Drugs` lectures.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Intestinal Disorders\n\n### Gastroenteritis\n- **Patho:** Inflammation of stomach and intestines, often viral or bacterial.\n- **Symptoms:** Severe diarrhea, vomiting.\n- **Priority Complication:** **Fluid Volume Deficit & Hypokalemia** (Low Potassium).\n  - *Signs of Hypokalemia:* Cardiac dysrhythmias, muscle weakness (e.g., K\u207a = 2.5 mEq/L is critical).\n  - *Signs of Dehydration:* Dry mucous membranes, dark urine, hypotension, tachycardia, lethargy.\n\n### Appendicitis\n- **Patho:** Inflammation of the appendix.\n- **Symptoms:** RLQ (Right Lower Quadrant) pain, rebound tenderness (McBurney's point), fever, nausea.\n> [!CAUTION]\n> **NEVER administer laxatives, enemas, or apply heat to the abdomen** if appendicitis is suspected! This can cause the appendix to rupture.\n> Sudden relief of pain indicates a **ruptured appendix** (Medical Emergency \u2192 Peritonitis).\n\n### Peritonitis\n- **Patho:** Inflammation of the peritoneum (often from perforated ulcer, ruptured appendix, or bowel perforation).\n- **Hallmark Signs:** \n  - **Rigid, board-like abdomen**\n  - Severe, sudden abdominal pain\n  - Absent bowel sounds\n  - Tachycardia and fever\n\n### Bowel Obstruction\n- **Mechanical:** Physical blockage (tumor, adhesions, hernia, fecal impaction).\n- **Non-Mechanical (Paralytic Ileus):** Lack of peristalsis (common post-surgery or due to hypokalemia).\n- **Symptoms:** High-pitched hyperactive bowel sounds *above* the obstruction, absent sounds *below*. Vomiting (can be fecal matter if lower obstruction), abdominal distension.\n- **Nursing:** NPO, NG tube for decompression, IV fluids.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Inflammatory Bowel Disease (IBD)\n\n### Crohn's Disease vs. Ulcerative Colitis\n| Feature | Crohn's Disease | Ulcerative Colitis (UC) |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Location** | Anywhere from mouth to anus (usually terminal ileum) | Begins in rectum, spreads continuously up the colon |\n| **Lesions** | \"Cobblestone\" appearance, skip lesions | Continuous inflammation, mucosal ulcers |\n| **Stools** | 5-6 loose stools/day, non-bloody | 10-20 liquid bloody stools/day |\n| **Complications**| Fistulas, strictures, severe malabsorption | Toxic megacolon, high risk for colon cancer |\n| **Cure** | No cure | Colectomy (removal of colon) is curative |\n\n### Diverticular Disease\n- **Diverticulosis:** Presence of pouches in colon wall (asymptomatic). *Diet:* High fiber.\n- **Diverticulitis:** Inflammation/infection of the pouches.\n  - *Symptoms:* LLQ (Left Lower Quadrant) pain, fever.\n  - *Diet during acute attack:* NPO or Clear liquids, low-fiber until inflammation resolves. Avoid seeds, nuts, popcorn.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Ostomy Care\n- **Stoma Appearance:** Should be beefy red, pink, and moist.\n  - *Call Provider:* If stoma is pale, purple, black, or dry (indicates ischemia/necrosis).\n- **Ileostomy:** Liquid stool (high risk for fluid/electrolyte imbalance).\n- **Colostomy:** More formed stool depending on location (Ascending = liquid, Descending/Sigmoid = formed).\n\n---\n\n## 4. Lower GI Pharmacology\n\n### \ud83d\udc8a Laxatives (For Constipation)\n> [!WARNING]\n> Laxatives are contraindicated in patients with severe, undiagnosed abdominal pain, nausea/vomiting, or suspected bowel obstruction/appendicitis.\n\n- **Stimulant Laxatives:** Bisacodyl (Dulcolax), Senna.\n  - *Action:* Irritates intestines to promote peristalsis. Relieves acute constipation.\n- **Osmotic Laxatives:** Polyethylene glycol (MiraLax), Lactulose.\n  - *Action:* Draws water into the intestine from surrounding tissues.\n- **Bulk-Forming Laxatives:** Psyllium (Metamucil).\n  - *Action:* Retains water within the stool. Safest for routine use.\n  - *Nursing:* **Must be given with a full glass of water** to prevent esophageal obstruction.\n- **Stool Softeners:** Docusate (Colace).\n  - *Action:* Draws water into stool to soften it. Used prophylactically (e.g., post-surgery to prevent straining).\n\n### \ud83d\udc8a Antidiarrheal Agents\n- **Action:** Reduces GI tract motility to allow mucosal lining to absorb nutrients, water, and electrolytes.\n- **Nursing:** \n  - *Do NOT use* to treat diarrhea caused by toxic substances or infectious organisms (e.g., C. diff); stopping diarrhea traps the toxin/bacteria in the body.\n  - Monitor closely for dehydration and electrolyte imbalances.\n\n### \ud83d\udc8a Medications for IBD (Crohn's/UC)\n- **Aminosalicylates (5-ASAs):** Sulfasalazine, Mesalamine. Decreases GI inflammation.\n- **Corticosteroids:** Prednisone. Used during acute exacerbations to quickly reduce severe inflammation.\n- **Immunosuppressants / Biologics:** Adalimumab (Humira), Infliximab (Remicade).\n";
